=== ''Black Widow'' (2021) ===
{{Main|Black Widow (2021 film){{!}}''Black Widow'' (2021 film)}}
[[Natasha Romanoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Natasha Romanoff]] finds herself alone and forced to confront a dangerous conspiracy with ties to her past. Pursued by a force that will stop at nothing to bring her down, Romanoff must deal with her history as a spy and the broken relationships left in her wake long before she became an [[Avengers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Avenger]].<ref name="SchaefferInverseJul2019" /><ref name="BWSynopsis" />

After exploring the backstory of [[Scarlett Johansson]]'s character Natasha Romanoff / Black Widow in ''[[Avengers: Age of Ultron]]'' (2015), [[Kevin Feige]] expressed interest in further exploring it in a solo film.<ref name="BlackWidowSolo" /> By January 2018, [[Jac Schaeffer]] was hired to write the script,<ref name="SchaefferVariety" /> with [[Cate Shortland]] hired to direct that July.<ref name="BWShortland" /> [[Ned Benson]] was rewriting the script the next February.<ref name="BWBenson" /> Schaeffer and Benson received story credit on the film, with [[Eric Pearson]] credited for the screenplay.<ref name="BWWriters" /> Filming began in May 2019 and concluded that October,<ref name="BWFilmingBegin" /><ref name="BWFilmingWrap" /> shooting in Norway, the United Kingdom, [[Budapest]], Morocco, and Georgia.<ref name="BWFilmingBegin" /><ref name="BWLondonFilming" /><ref name="BWFilmingLocations" /> ''Black Widow'' premiered on June 29, 2021, at various red carpet fan events in London, Los Angeles, Melbourne, and New York City,<ref name="BWFanPremiereABC" /><ref name="BWFanPremieresReuters" /> and was released in the United States on July 9, 2021, in theaters and on [[Disney+]] with [[Disney+ Premier Access|Premier Access]].<ref name="BWShangChiRelease" />

''Black Widow'' is set in 2016, mostly taking place between the main plot of ''[[Captain America: Civil War]]'' (2016) and its final scene.<ref name="BWTimeline" /> [[William Hurt]] reprises his role as [[Thaddeus Ross (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Thaddeus Ross]] from previous MCU films.<ref name="HurtBW" /> ''Black Widow''{{'s}} [[post-credits scene]] features [[Julia Louis-Dreyfus]], uncredited, as [[Valentina Allegra de Fontaine (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Valentina Allegra de Fontaine]] from the series ''[[The Falcon and the Winter Soldier]]'' (2021),<ref name="LouisDreyfusBW" /> and sets up [[Florence Pugh]]'s appearance in the series ''[[Hawkeye (miniseries)|Hawkeye]]'' (2021) as [[Yelena Belova (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Yelena Belova]].<ref name="BWPostCredits" /> [[Jeremy Renner]] has an uncredited voice [[cameo appearance|cameo]] in his MCU role of [[Clint Barton (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Clint Barton / Hawkeye]], while a picture of him is also featured.<ref name="BWPostCreditsRenner" />

=== ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' (2021) ===
{{Main|Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings{{!}}''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings''}}
When [[Shang-Chi (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Shang-Chi]] is drawn into the clandestine [[Ten Rings (organization)|Ten Rings]] organization, he is forced to confront the past he thought he left behind.<ref name="ShangChiSynopsis" />

By December 2018, [[Marvel Studios]] was actively developing their first Asian-led film for Shang-Chi, with [[Dave Callaham]] hired to write the screenplay,<ref name="CallahamShangChi" /> and [[Destin Daniel Cretton]] to direct by March 2019.<ref name="DestinDanielCretton" /> At [[San Diego Comic-Con]] that July, [[Simu Liu]] was revealed to play the [[title role]], along with [[Tony Leung Chiu-wai|Tony Leung]] as [[Wenwu]].<ref name="THRPhase4SDCC" /><ref name="ShangChiSynopsis" /> Filming began in February 2020,<ref name="ShangChiFilmingBegin" /><ref name="ShangChiFilmingBegin2" /> but was halted in March due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name="ShangChiFilmingSuspended" /> Production resumed in August and concluded that October.<ref name="ShangChiFilmingRestart" /><ref name="ShangChiFilmingWrap" /> Shooting occurred in Australia and San Francisco.<ref name="ShangChiFilmingBegin" /><ref name="ShangChiSanFranFilming" /> In April 2021, Cretton was revealed as a credited writer along with Callaham and [[Andrew Lanham]].<ref name="ShangChiWriters" /><ref name="ShangChiWritersApr2021" /> ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' premiered in Los Angeles on August 16, 2021,<ref name="ShangChiPremiere" /> and was released in the United States on September 3, 2021.<ref name="BWShangChiRelease" />

''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' is set after the events of ''[[Avengers: Endgame]]'' (2019),<ref name="ShangChiFandango" /> during the days leading to the [[Qingming Festival]] in early April.<ref name="ShangChiQingmingFestival" /> [[Benedict Wong]] reprises his role as [[Wong (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Wong]] from previous MCU films,<ref name="AbominationWongShangChi" /> along with [[Ben Kingsley]] as [[Trevor Slattery]], an impostor posing as the [[Mandarin (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Mandarin]], from ''[[Iron Man 3]]'' (2013) and the [[Marvel One-Shot]] ''[[All Hail the King]]'' (2014).<ref name="KingsleyShangChi" /> The Ten Rings organization has been featured or referenced in ''[[Iron Man (2008 film)|Iron Man]]'' (2008), ''[[Iron Man 2]]'' (2010), ''All Hail the King'', and ''[[Ant-Man (film)|Ant-Man]]'' (2015).<ref name="TenRingsEggs" /> [[Tim Roth]] also provided uncredited vocals for [[Abomination (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Emil Blonsky / Abomination]], reprising the role from ''[[The Incredible Hulk (film)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' (2008),<ref name="AbominationWongShangChi" /><ref name="RothShangChi" /> while the mid-credits scene features [[Mark Ruffalo]] and [[Brie Larson]], uncredited, in their respective MCU roles of [[Bruce Banner (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Bruce Banner]] and [[Carol Danvers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Carol Danvers / Captain Marvel]].<ref name="LarsonRuffaloShangChi" />

=== ''Eternals'' (2021) ===
{{Main|Eternals (film){{!}}''Eternals'' (film)}}
After the return of half the population ignites "the emergence", the [[Eternals (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Eternals]]—an immortal alien race created by the [[Celestials (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Celestials]] who have secretly lived on Earth for over 7,000 years—reunite to protect humanity from their evil counterparts, the [[Deviants (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Deviants]].<ref name="EternalsSynopsis" /><ref name="EternalsTHRFinalTrailer" />

By early 2018, Marvel Studios was developing a film for the Eternals, with [[Kaz Firpo]] and Ryan Firpo writing the script to focus on a love story between the characters [[Sersi (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Sersi]] and [[Ikaris (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Ikaris]].<ref name="Eternals" /><ref name="EternalsWriters" /><ref name="EternalsZhao" /> Late that September, [[Chloé Zhao]] was hired to direct ''The Eternals'',<ref name="EternalsZhao" /> and also served as the film's credited writer along with [[Patrick Burleigh]] and the Firpos.<ref name="EternalsWritingCredits" /><ref name="EternalsWGAWritingCredits" /> Filming occurred from July 2019 to February 2020, shooting throughout [[England]].<ref name="EternalsFilming" /><ref name="EternalsFilmingWrap" /> The main cast, headlined by [[Richard Madden]] as Ikaris and [[Angelina Jolie]] as [[Thena (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Thena]], was announced at the July 2019 San Diego Comic-Con,<ref name="THRPhase4SDCC" /> with [[Gemma Chan]] cast as Sersi the next month.<ref name="D232019EternalsBP2" /> The title was shortened in August 2020.<ref name="EternalsTitleShorten" /> ''Eternals'' premiered in Los Angeles on October 18, 2021,<ref name="EternalsPremiere" /> and was released in the United States on November 5.<ref name="Phase4DelayAgain" />

''Eternals'' takes place around the same time as ''The Falcon and the Winter Soldier'' and ''[[Spider-Man: Far From Home]]'' (2019), six to eight months after ''Avengers: Endgame'' in 2024.<ref name="EternalsTimeline2" /><ref name="EternalsTimeline" /> The mid-credits scene features [[Harry Styles]] as [[Thanos (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Thanos]]'s brother [[Eros (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Eros / Starfox]] and [[Patton Oswalt]] as [[Pip the Troll (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Pip the Troll]],<ref name="EternalsPostCredits" /><ref name="OswaltPipMocap" /> while [[Mahershala Ali]] has an uncredited cameo as the voice of [[Blade (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Blade]] in the post-credits scene, before starring in the film ''[[Blade (upcoming film)|Blade]]'' (2025).<ref name="EternalsPostCredits" />

=== ''Spider-Man: No Way Home'' (2021) ===
{{Main|Spider-Man: No Way Home{{!}}''Spider-Man: No Way Home''}}
[[File:Jon Watts by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Jon Watts]], director of the ''Spider-Man'' films]]
[[Peter Parker (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Peter Parker]]'s life and reputation are turned upside down following his identity being exposed at the hands of [[Quentin Beck (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Mysterio]]. Seeking help from [[Stephen Strange (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Stephen Strange]] to try and fix everything, things soon become much more dangerous when the [[Multiverse (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|multiverse]] breaks open, allowing villains from alternate realities who have previously fought versions of Spider-Man to arrive.<ref name="NWHSynopsis" /><ref name="NWHSynopsis2" />

A third MCU ''Spider-Man'' film was planned by early 2017 to be set during Peter Parker's senior year of high school,<ref name="/FilmFFHSequel" /><ref name="FFHSequelSeniorYear" /> with Feige later saying it would tell "a Peter Parker story" not previously done on film due to the mid-credits scene in ''Spider-Man: Far From Home''.<ref name="FeigeFFHSequel" /> By August 2019, [[Chris McKenna (writer)|Chris McKenna]] and [[Erik Sommers]] were writing the script while Disney and Sony split on adjusting their agreement over Marvel Studios' involvement in Spider-Man films,<ref name="FFHSequelWriters" /><ref name="NoNewSonyDealAug2019" /> but announced the next month they would co-produce the film, with [[Tom Holland]] returning to star,<ref name="DisneySonySpidey3" /> along with [[Jon Watts]] as director by June 2020.<ref name="WattsSM3Confirm" /> Filming began in October 2020 in [[New York City]],<ref name="Spidey3FilmingStart" /> before moving to [[Trilith Studios]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] later that month.<ref name="SM3AtlantaFilming" /><ref name="SM3Trilith" /> The title was officially announced in February 2021,<ref name="NoWayHome" /> before filming concluded in late March.<ref name="NWHFilmingWrap" /> Producer [[Amy Pascal]] described the film as "the culmination of the ''Homecoming'' trilogy".<ref name="PascalNov2021Fandango" /> ''Spider-Man: No Way Home'' premiered in Los Angeles on December 13, 2021,<ref name="NWHPremiere" /> and was released in the United States on December 17, 2021.<ref name="NoWayHome" />

''Spider-Man: No Way Home'' begins immediately after the events of ''Spider-Man: Far From Home'', and continues over late 2024,<ref name="NWHTimeline" /> while also tying into ''[[Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness]]'' (2022);<ref name="DS2NWH" /> [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] and Benedict Wong reprise their roles as Dr. Stephen Strange and Wong, respectively.<ref name="CumberbatchSM3" /><ref name="NWHVarietyTrailer" /> ''No Way Home'' explores the concept of the multiverse and ties the MCU to past ''Spider-Man'' film series, with [[Tobey Maguire]] and [[Andrew Garfield]] returning as their versions of Spider-Man from [[Sam Raimi]]'s [[Spider-Man (2002 film series)|''Spider-Man'' trilogy]] and [[Marc Webb]]'s [[The Amazing Spider-Man (film series)|''The Amazing Spider-Man'' films]],<ref name="NWHMaguireGarfield" /> who were respectively dubbed "[[Peter Parker (2002 film series character)|Peter-Two]]" and "[[Peter Parker (The Amazing Spider-Man film series)|Peter-Three]]",<ref name="Peter2Peter3" /> alongside [[Willem Dafoe]] as [[Norman Osborn (2002 film series character)|Norman Osborn / Green Goblin]], [[Alfred Molina]] as [[Otto Octavius (film character)|Otto Octavius / Doctor Octopus]], and [[Thomas Haden Church]] as [[Flint Marko (Sam Raimi film series)|Flint Marko / Sandman]] from the Raimi films,<ref name="NWHPastVillains" /> and [[Rhys Ifans]] as [[Curt Connors (The Amazing Spider-Man film series)|Curt Connors / Lizard]] and [[Jamie Foxx]] as [[Max Dillon (The Amazing Spider-Man film series)|Max Dillon / Electro]] from the Webb films.<ref name="NWHPastVillains" /> [[Charlie Cox]] appears as [[Matt Murdock (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Matt Murdock]], reprising the role from [[Marvel Television]]'s [[Marvel's Netflix television series|Netflix series]],<ref name="CoxNWH" /> while [[Tom Hardy]] appears, uncredited, in the [[mid-credits scene]] as [[Venom (Sony's Spider-Man Universe)|Eddie Brock / Venom]], reprising his role from [[Sony's Spider-Man Universe]].<ref name="NWHPostCreditsVenom" />

=== ''Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness'' (2022) ===
{{Main|Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness{{!}}''Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness''}}
Dr. Stephen Strange protects [[America Chavez (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|America Chavez]], a teenager capable of traveling between universes in the [[Multiverse (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|multiverse]], from [[Wanda Maximoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Wanda Maximoff / Scarlet Witch]].<ref name="DS2Synopsis" />

By December 2018, ''[[Doctor Strange (2016 film)|Doctor Strange]]'' (2016) director and co-writer [[Scott Derrickson]] signed to direct a sequel, with Benedict Cumberbatch reprising his title role.<ref name="DerricksonDS2" /> The title was officially announced at the 2019 San Diego Comic-Con, along with [[Elizabeth Olsen]]'s involvement.<ref name="THRPhase4SDCC" /> In January 2020, Derrickson stepped down as director over creative differences, but remained an executive producer.<ref name="DerricksonDS2Exit" /> The next month, Sam Raimi signed on to direct,<ref name="RaimiDS2" /><ref name="WaldronVanityFair" /> and ''[[Loki (TV series)|Loki]]'' (2021) [[head writer]] [[Michael Waldron]] joined to rewrite the script;<ref name="WaldronDS2" /> Raimi confirmed his involvement in April 2020.<ref name="RaimiDS2Confirm" /> Filming began by November 2020 in [[London]],<ref name="THRNov2020Updates" /><ref name="DS2FilmingOlsen" /> but was halted in January 2021 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref name="DS2FilmingHalt" /> Production resumed by that March,<ref name="DS2FilmingResume" /> and concluded in mid-April 2021 in [[Somerset]].<ref name="DS2FilmingEnd" /> Shooting also occurred at [[Longcross Studios]] in [[Surrey]].<ref name="DS2LongcrossFilming" /> ''Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness'' premiered in Hollywood on May 2, 2022,<ref name="DSMoMPremiere" /> and was released in the United States on May 6, 2022.<ref name="October2021Delay" />

''Doctor Strange in the Multiverse of Madness'' is set after the events of ''Spider-Man: No Way Home''.<ref name="MoMTimeline" /><ref name="MarvelDisney+TimelineJun2022" /> Elizabeth Olsen co-stars as Wanda Maximoff / Scarlet Witch,<ref name="DS2WandaVision" /> continuing from her appearance in the series ''[[WandaVision]]'' (2021),<ref name="EWWVNov2020CoverStory" /> with Julian Hilliard and [[Jett Klyne]] portraying alternate versions of Maximoff's sons [[Billy Maximoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Billy]] and [[Tommy Maximoff (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Tommy]], respectively.<ref name="WandaSonsDS2" /> The film introduces the [[Illuminati (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Illuminati]], a group of heroes from the alternate universe [[Earth-838]], which consists of [[Patrick Stewart]] as [[Charles Xavier (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Charles Xavier / Professor X]] (after playing a different version of the character in [[20th Century Fox]]'s [[X-Men (film series)|''X-Men'' film series]]), [[Hayley Atwell]] as [[Captain Carter|Peggy Carter / Captain Carter]] (after voicing a similar version in the animated series ''[[What If...? (TV series)|What If...?]]''), [[Lashana Lynch]] as [[Maria Rambeau|Maria Rambeau / Captain Marvel]] (after playing the main MCU version of Rambeau in ''[[Captain Marvel (film)|Captain Marvel]]''), [[Anson Mount]] as [[Black Bolt (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Blackagar Boltagon / Black Bolt]] (after playing another version of Black Bolt in [[Marvel's ABC television series]] ''[[Inhumans (TV series)|Inhumans]]''), and [[John Krasinski]] as [[Reed Richards (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Reed Richards / Mister Fantastic]], a member of the [[Fantastic Four (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Fantastic Four]].<ref name="IlluminatiMoM" />

=== ''Thor: Love and Thunder'' (2022) ===
{{Main|Thor: Love and Thunder{{!}}''Thor: Love and Thunder''}}
[[File:Taika Waititi by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Taika Waititi]], director of ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' and ''[[Thor: Love and Thunder]]'']]
[[Thor (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Thor]] attempts to find inner peace but ends up recruiting [[Valkyrie (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Valkyrie]], [[Korg (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Korg]], and [[Jane Foster (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Jane Foster]]—who has become the [[Mighty Thor]]—to help stop [[Gorr (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Gorr the God Butcher]] from eliminating all gods.<ref name="ThorLTSynopsis" />

[[Chris Hemsworth]] expressed ongoing interest to return as Thor in January 2018, at the time his Marvel Studios contract had come to an end.<ref name="HemsworthFuture" /> After previously directing ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' (2017), [[Taika Waititi]] signed on to write and direct a fourth ''[[Thor (film)|Thor]]'' film in July 2019,<ref name="WaititiThor4" /> and the title was officially announced at [[San Diego Comic-Con]] later that month, with Hemsworth returning alongside [[Tessa Thompson]] as Valkyrie and [[Natalie Portman]] as Jane Foster, who becomes the superhero the Mighty Thor.<ref name="HemsworthPortmanThor4" /><ref name="MightyThor" /> [[Jennifer Kaytin Robinson]] joined to co-write the script with Waititi in February 2020.<ref name="RobinsonVariety" /><ref name="ThorLaTWritersCredits" /> Filming began late January 2021 in Australia,<ref name="ThorLTFilmingStart" /> and concluded that June.<ref name="ThorLTFilmingWrap" /> ''Thor: Love and Thunder'' premiered in Los Angeles on June 23, 2022,<ref name="ThorLTPremiere" /> and was released in the United States on July 8, 2022.<ref name="October2021Delay" />

''Thor: Love and Thunder'' is set after the events of ''Avengers: Endgame'',<ref name="ThorLTSynopsis" /> eight and a half years after Thor broke up with Foster, which had occurred by ''Ragnarok'',<ref name="ThorLTTimeline8Years" /> and "a few weeks" since Thor joined the [[Guardians of the Galaxy (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Guardians of the Galaxy]],<ref name="GotGHSTimeline2" /> who appear in the film, with [[Chris Pratt]], [[Karen Gillan]], [[Dave Bautista]], [[Pom Klementieff]], [[Sean Gunn]], [[Vin Diesel]], and [[Bradley Cooper]] reprising their respective MCU roles as [[Peter Quill (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Peter Quill / Star-Lord]], [[Nebula (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Nebula]], [[Drax (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Drax the Destroyer]], [[Mantis (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Mantis]], [[Kraglin Obfonteri]], [[Groot (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Groot]], and [[Rocket (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Rocket]].<ref name="GuardiansLaT" /> Daley Pearson appears as Darryl, after first portraying the role in the ''[[Team Thor]]'' short films.<ref name="ThorLaTColliderEasterEggs" />

=== ''Black Panther: Wakanda Forever'' (2022) ===
{{Main|Black Panther: Wakanda Forever{{!}}''Black Panther: Wakanda Forever''}}
[[File:Ryan Coogler by Gage Skidmore (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Ryan Coogler]], director of ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' and ''[[Black Panther: Wakanda Forever]]'']]
The leaders of the kingdom of [[Wakanda (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Wakanda]] fight to protect their nation in the wake of King [[T'Challa (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|T'Challa]]'s death,<ref name="BP2Premise" /> and a new threat emerges from the hidden undersea nation of [[Talokan (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Talokan]].<ref name="BP2Premise2" />

By October 2018, [[Ryan Coogler]] signed on to write and direct a sequel to ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]]'' (2018).<ref name="CooglerBPSequel" /> [[Joe Robert Cole]] also returned for the film to once again co-write the screenplay with Coogler.<ref name="FeigeRTJul2021" /> Feige confirmed the film was in development by mid-2019 with the placeholder title ''Black Panther II''.<ref name="BPSequelConfirmed" /><ref name="D232019EternalsBP2" /> Plans for the film changed in August 2020 when ''Black Panther'' star [[Chadwick Boseman]] died from [[colon cancer]],<ref name="BP2ProductionBosemanDeath" /> with his role as [[T'Challa (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|T'Challa]] not recast.<ref name="BP2Dec2020" /> Some of the main returning cast members were confirmed by that November,<ref name="THRNov2020Updates" /> with [[Letitia Wright]] headlining the film as [[Shuri (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Shuri / Black Panther]].<ref name="THRNov2020Updates" /><ref name="ShuriBlackPanther" /> The title, ''Black Panther: Wakanda Forever'', was revealed in May 2021.<ref name="May2021DatesTitles" /> Production began in late June 2021 at Trilith Studios in Atlanta,<ref name="BP2ProductionStart" /> and lasted until early November 2021,<ref name="BP2FilmingHiatus" /> before a hiatus began later that month.<ref name="BP2FilmingHiatus2" /> Filming resumed in mid-January 2022.<ref name="BP2FilmingResume" /> Shooting also occurred in [[Boston]] and [[Worcester, Massachusetts]],<ref name="BP2BostonFilming" /><ref name="BP2WorcesterFilming" /> and in [[Brunswick, Georgia]],<ref name="BP2BrunswickFilming" /> before wrapping in Puerto Rico in March 2022.<ref name="BPWFWrap" /> ''Black Panther: Wakanda Forever'' premiered in Hollywood on October 26, 2022,<ref name="BPWFPremiere" /> and was released on November 11, 2022.<ref name="October2021Delay" />

''Black Panther: Wakanda Forever'' is set after the events of ''Spider-Man: No Way Home'', and "potentially concurrent" with ''Love and Thunder'' and ''[[Ant-Man and the Wasp: Quantumania]]'' (2023) according to producer [[Nate Moore (film producer)|Nate Moore]].<ref name="BP2Timeline" /> [[Dominique Thorne]] appears as [[Riri Williams (Marvel Cinematic Universe)|Riri Williams / Ironheart]], ahead of starring in the Disney+ series ''[[Ironheart (miniseries)|Ironheart]]'' (2025).<ref name="ThorneBP2" /> Julia Louis-Dreyfus reprises her MCU role as Valentina Allegra de Fontaine, now serving as the director of the [[CIA]].<ref name="LouisDreyfusBP2" />
{{clear}}

