On May 8, [[United States Assistant Attorney General|Assistant Attorney General]] [[Stephen Boyd (attorney)|Stephen Boyd]] wrote Nadler that Barr would ask Trump to invoke executive privilege to withhold the full report if the Judiciary Committee proceeded to vote on a contempt charge.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=mkraju |number=1125952217012482049 |title=NEW: Barr threatens to ask the WH to invoke executive privilege over the Democrats' demands for the Mueller report if the committee votes to hold him in contempt tomorrow. Vote is still on. |first=Manu |last=Raju |author-link=Manu Raju |access-date=May 8, 2019 |date=May 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/442635-doj-tells-house-judiciary-to-cancel-contempt-vote-or-it-will-ask |title=DOJ threatens executive privilege over Mueller report if Dems carry out contempt vote  |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=May 7, 2019 |first=Olivia |last=Beavers |access-date=May 22, 2019 }}</ref> Boyd wrote in the letter to Nadler saying "We are disappointed that you have rejected the Department of Justice's request to delay the vote of the Committee on the Judiciary on a contempt finding against the Attorney General this morning ... Accordingly, this is to advise you that the President has asserted executive privilege over the entirety of the subpoenaed materials."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/PrivilegeLetter.pdf |title=Assistant Attorney General Stephen E. Boyd's letter to House Judiciary Committee Chairman Jerry Nadler |access-date=May 22, 2019 |date=May 8, 2019  }}</ref> Also on May 8, Barr wrote a letter to Trump to "request that you make protective assertion of executive privilege with respect to Department of Justice documents recently subpoenaed by the Committee on the Judiciary of the House of Representatives."<ref name=":19" /> On May 8, Trump invoked [[executive privilege]] for those documents at Barr's request.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/08/us/politics/congress-contempt-barr.html|title=Trump Asserts Executive Privilege Over Full Mueller Report|last=Fandos|first=Nicholas|date=May 8, 2019|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=May 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=":19">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/08/trump-will-assert-executive-privilege-over-mueller-report-materials.html|title=Trump will assert 'executive privilege' over Mueller report|last=Mangan|first=Dan|date=May 8, 2019|website=[[CNBC]] |language=en|access-date=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Trump's announcement of executive privilege came just hours before the House Judiciary Committee planned to vote on whether to hold Barr in contempt. The Committee voted unanimously to reject this assertion of executive privilege and approved a motion put forward by Rep. [[Matt Gaetz]] (R-Fl) which states that a vote to hold Barr in contempt would not "be construed as a directive for the Attorney General to violate Federal law or rules".<ref name=may8cbs>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/barr-in-contempt-of-congress-hearing-judiciary-committee-vote-attorney-general-barr-mueller-report-today-2019-05-08/|title=House Judiciary votes to hold Barr in contempt for defying Mueller report subpoena|website=[[CBS News]] |first1=Emily |last1=Tillett |first2=Grace |last2=Segers |date=May 8, 2019 |access-date=May 22, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2019/may/8/house-judiciary-committee-approves-amendment-oppos/|title=House Judiciary Committee approves amendment opposing Trump's assertion of executive privilege|work=[[The Washington Times]] |first=Jeff |last=Mordock |date=May 8, 2019 |access-date=May 22, 2019 }}</ref> In a 24–16 vote, the House Judiciary Committee approved a motion of Contempt of Congress against Barr.<ref>{{cite news |date=May 8, 2019 |first1=Mike |last1=Memoli |first2=Alex |last2=Moe |first3=Rebecca |last3=Shabad |first4=Jamie |last4=Knodel |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/justice-department-set-ask-executive-privilege-mueller-report-n1003146|title=House Judiciary Committee votes to hold Barr in contempt after Trump asserts executive privilege|website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=May 22, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=may8cbs />

==== Hope Hicks testimony ====
A day before [[Hope Hicks]] was expected to testify behind closed doors before the House Intelligence Committee on June 18, 2019, White House Counsel [[Pat Cipollone]] sent a letter to Committee chairman Jerry Nadler that President Trump instructed Hicks to not answer questions pertaining to her work at the White House.<ref name=":10">{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/449213-white-house-says-hope-hicks-immune-from-compelled-congressional|title=White House says Hope Hicks 'immune' from compelled congressional testimony|last=Chalfant|first=Morgan|date=June 18, 2019 |website=TheHill|access-date=June 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=June 18, 2019 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/18/politics/hope-hicks-testimony-trump-hush-money-affairs/index.html|title=White House will assert immunity for Hope Hicks during congressional testimony |first1=Manu |last1=Raju |first2=Jeremy |last2=Herb |first3=Pamela |last3=Brown |website=CNN |access-date=June 19, 2019}}</ref> "Ms. Hicks is absolutely immune from being compelled to testify before Congress with respect to matters occurring during her service as a senior adviser to the President," Cipollone says. "Because of this constitutional immunity, and in order to protect the prerogatives of the Office of the President, the President has directed Ms. Hicks not to answer questions before the Committee relating to the time of her service as a senior adviser to the President."<ref name=":10" />

In the letter, Cipollone cited various Office of Legal Counsel (OLC) opinions arguing that Hicks is immune from compelled testimony, including one issued by the Justice Department in May that Trump cited when instructing former White House counsel Don McGahn not to testify before the committee pursuant to a subpoena. Cipollone also indicated that the White House may try to block Hicks from answering questions about her time on the presidential transition team because of potential executive privilege concerns. "Much of Ms. Hicks's work during this period involved discussions with the President-elect and his staff relating to the decisions the President-elect would be making once he assumed office," Cipollone wrote. "Accordingly, her responses to specific questions about this period would likely implicate executive branch confidentiality interests concerning that decisionmaking process," he wrote. "In order to preserve the President's ability to assert executive privilege over such information, a member of my office will attend Ms. Hicks's testimony on June 19."<ref name=":10" />

During Hicks' testimony, lawyers for the Trump administration forbade Hicks from answering questions 155 times, claiming that due to "absolute immunity", Hicks "may not speak about anything that occurred during the time of her employment in the White House as a close adviser to the President".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shabad |first1=Rebecca |title=Hope Hicks stopped 155 times by White House lawyers from answering lawmakers' questions |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/democrats-release-273-page-transcript-closed-door-interview-hope-hicks-n1020066 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=June 21, 2019 |date=June 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Stahl |first1=Jeremy |title=This Passage From Hope Hicks' Testimony Crystallizes the Inanity of the Democrats' Impeachment Stance |date=June 20, 2019 |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/06/hope-hicks-testimony-nancy-pelosi-impeachment-futility.html |website=[[Slate (website)|Slate]] |access-date=June 21, 2019}}</ref>

=== Senate Judiciary Committee ===
On May 1, Attorney General Barr testified before the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]]. Barr said he "didn't exonerate" Trump on obstruction as that was not the role of the Justice Department. Barr explained his decision that there was not enough evidence for Trump to be charged with obstruction by citing that the president did not commit an underlying crime related to Russia.<ref name="APMay1Test">{{cite web |last1=Day |first1=Chad |title=Key takeaways from AG Barr's testimony, Mueller's letter |url=https://apnews.com/ec455a7ba1c846deaf8a2616f7754698 |date=May 2, 2019 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=May 2, 2019}}</ref>

Then California Democratic Senator and now [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Kamala Harris]] questioned why neither Barr nor Rosenstein reviewed the underlying evidence in the report. "We accepted the statements in the report as the factual record. We did not go underneath it to see whether or not they were accurate, we accepted it as accurate," Barr said. He asserted this approach was common DOJ practice.<ref name="WaPoFam">{{Cite news |first=Philip |last=Bump |date=May 1, 2019 |access-date=May 6, 2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/05/01/barrs-conclusions-are-undercut-by-his-lack-familiarity-with-details-muellers-probe/ |title=Analysis &#124; Barr's conclusions are undercut by his lack of familiarity with details of Mueller's probe |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |archive-date=February 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210216175556/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/05/01/barrs-conclusions-are-undercut-by-his-lack-familiarity-with-details-muellers-probe/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |access-date=May 6, 2019 |url=https://thehill.com/policy/national-security/441643-barr-says-he-didnt-review-underlying-evidence-of-mueller-report|title=Barr says he didn't review underlying evidence of Mueller report before making obstruction call|first=Olivia|last=Beavers|date=May 1, 2019|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref> Harris also asked Barr if Rosenstein had been cleared by ethics officials to be involved in the decision to not charge Trump of obstruction, given that Rosenstein was a witness to the investigation regarding James Comey's firing. Barr with the help of his aides concluded by saying "He was the acting attorney general on the Mueller investigation...I'm informed that before I arrived, he had been cleared by the ethics officials."<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Meg |last1=Wagner |first2=Veronica |last2=Rocha |first3=Brian |last3=Ries |first4=Amanda |last4=Wills |url=https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/barr-testimony-mueller-report/index.html|title=William Barr testifies on the Mueller report: Live updates|date=May 1, 2019 |website=[[CNN]]|language=en|access-date=May 2, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |first1=Meg |last1=Wagner |first2=Veronica |last2=Rocha |first3=Brian |last3=Ries |first4=Amanda |last4=Wills |url= https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/barr-testimony-mueller-report/h_62634cbfb0ff94a9a3085a41aeb90ea6 |title=Harris grills Barr about Rod Rosenstein's dual roles as investigation supervisor and witness|date=May 1, 2019 |website=[[CNN]]|language=en|access-date=May 2, 2019 }}</ref>

On the question of whether Trump could have ended the investigation, Barr said "the situation of the President, who has constitutional authority to supervise proceedings, if in fact a proceeding was not well founded, if it was a groundless proceeding, if it was based on false allegations, the President does not have to sit there, constitutionally, and allow it to run its course." He added, "The President could terminate that proceeding, and it would not be a corrupt intent, because he was being falsely accused.<ref name="APMay1Test" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Kate |title=Clinton: Barr's argument for the President being able to fire investigators is 'the road to tyranny' |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/05/01/politics/hillary-clinton-barr-tyranny/index.html |date=May 2, 2019 |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=May 2, 2019}}</ref> He later said that Trump "knew [the accusations against him] were false. And he felt this investigation was unfair, propelled by his political opponents and was hampering his ability to govern. That is not a corrupt motive for replacing an independent counsel".<ref name="UPIunfair">{{cite web |last1=Sakelaris |first1=Nicholas |last2=Haynes |first2=Danielle |title=AG William Barr defends handling of Mueller report at Senate hearing |date=May 1, 2019 |url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/US/2019/05/01/AG-William-Barr-defends-handling-of-Mueller-report-at-Senate-hearing/7391556705495/ |website=[[United Press International]] |access-date=May 2, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Politico]]'' described these comments as "Barr's expansive view of presidential authority to meddle in investigations".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheney |first1=Kyle |last2=Desiderio |first2=Andrew |title=The Barr-Mueller breakup: AG works to discredit special counsel |date=May 1, 2019 |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/01/barr-hearing-mueller-report-1295274 |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=May 2, 2019}}</ref> ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' argued against Barr's "perverse conclusion" because first, "Trump could not possibly know that an investigation was unfounded"; second, "Mueller did not say Trump was innocent"; and third, "Trump's obstruction was quite possibly one of the reasons Mueller failed to establish underlying crimes".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chait |first1=Jonathan |title=Barr: It's Not Obstruction of Justice If the Obstruction Works |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/05/barr-its-not-obstruction-of-justice-if-obstruction-works.html |date=May 1, 2019 |website=New York|access-date=May 2, 2019}}</ref>

Senator [[Richard Blumenthal]] asked Barr if he or his staff took notes on his March 28 call with Mueller. Barr confirmed there "were notes taken of the call", then told the committee that he would not share the notes with them: "Why should you have them?"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lybrand |first1=Holmes |title=Fact check: Can Congress get Barr's notes? |date=May 2, 2019 |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/05/02/politics/fact-check-barr-congress-mueller-call/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref>

[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[Nancy Pelosi]] commented on Barr's testimony and accused Barr of lying before Congress. "What is deadly serious about it is the attorney general of the United States of America is not telling the truth to the Congress of the United States. That's a crime," Pelosi told reporters. "He lied to Congress. If anybody else did that, it would be considered a crime. Nobody is above the law," Pelosi said. Department of Justice spokeswoman Kerri Kupec responded to Pelosi's remarks and said that a "baseless attack on the Attorney General is reckless, irresponsible and false."<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/02/nancy-pelosi-accuses-william-barr-of-committing-a-crime.html|title=Nancy Pelosi accuses William Barr of committing a crime|last=Pramuk|first=Jacob|date=May 2, 2019|website=[[CNBC]]|language=en|access-date=May 2, 2019 }}</ref> According to [[CNBC]], Pelosi's remarks were talking about Barr's comments in his April 9 testimony. Representative [[Charlie Crist]]: "Reports have emerged recently, general, that members of the special counsel's team are frustrated at some level with the limited information included in your March 24 letter. ... Do you know what they are referencing with that?" Barr: "No, I don't. I think I think, I suspect that they probably wanted more put out, but in my view I was not interested in putting out summaries."<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/us/politics/william-barr-testimony-factcheck.html|title=6 Evasive or Inaccurate Statements in Barr's Senate Testimony|last=Qiu|first=Linda|date=May 1, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=May 2, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

On May 8, 2019, the Senate Judiciary Committee subpoenaed [[Donald Trump Jr.]] to answer questions surrounding abandoned developments of a [[Trump Tower Moscow|Trump Tower in Moscow]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/08/senate-intelligence-committee-subpoenas-donald-trump-jr.html|title=Senate Intelligence Committee subpoenas Donald Trump Jr. to answer questions about prior claim to have limited role in Trump Tower Moscow deal |first1=Dan |last1=Mangan |first2=Brian |last2=Schwartz |first3=Kevin |last3=Breuninger|date=May 8, 2019|website=[[CNBC]]|access-date=May 8, 2019}}</ref> Trump Jr. has testified before the Committee<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Trump%20Jr%20Transcript_redacted.pdf |title=Interview of: Donald J. Trump, Jr. |work=[[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary]] |date=September 7, 2017 |access-date=May 22, 2019 }}</ref> on the same topic and related matters in September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/09/07/i-believed-that-i-should-at-least-hear-them-out-donald-trump-jr-s-testament-to-his-own-naivete-on-russia-annotated/ |title=Donald Trump Jr.'s testament to his own naivete on Russia, annotated |last=Phillips |first=Amber |date=September 7, 2017 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=May 12, 2019 |archive-date=May 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513024201/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/09/07/i-believed-that-i-should-at-least-hear-them-out-donald-trump-jr-s-testament-to-his-own-naivete-on-russia-annotated/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Trump Jr. is expected to testify sometime in June for a second closed-door interview. According to the ''Washington Post'': "Trump Jr. will testify for up to four hours and address a limited number of questions, these people said on the condition of anonymity to discuss sensitive negotiations."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/donald-trump-jr-agrees-to-testify-before-the-senate-intelligence-committee-again/2019/05/14/2efd4574-7686-11e9-bd25-c989555e7766_story.html |title=Donald Trump Jr. agrees to testify before the Senate Intelligence Committee again |last1=Demirjian |last2=Parker |last3=Hamburger |first1=Karoun |first2=Ashley |first3=Tom |date=May 14, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=May 31, 2019 |archive-date=February 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210216175605/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/donald-trump-jr-agrees-to-testify-before-the-senate-intelligence-committee-again/2019/05/14/2efd4574-7686-11e9-bd25-c989555e7766_story.html?noredirect=on |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== House Intelligence Committee ===
The [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|House Intelligence Committee]] announced on May 14, 2019, that it would investigate whether attorneys for Trump and his family members{{snd}}[[Jay Sekulow]], [[Alan Futerfas]], [[Abbe Lowell]] and [[Alan Garten]]{{snd}}"reviewed, shaped and edited" [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]]'s false testimony{{Clarify|reason=|date=May 2019}} to Congress.<ref>{{Cite news |date=May 14, 2019 |first=Andrew |last=Desiderio |access-date=May 22, 2019 |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/14/house-intel-trump-attorneys-obstruction-1322468|title=House Intel probing Trump attorneys for possible obstruction|website=[[Politico]] }}</ref>

On June 25, 2019, House Intelligence Committee Chairman, [[Adam Schiff]], and chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, Jerry Nadler, both publicly announced that Mueller agreed to publicly testify before House Judiciary and Intelligence Committees on July 17.<ref name=":22" />

On July 24, 2019, Mueller testified before the House Intelligence Committee after being subpoenaed.<ref name=":23" /> When asked as to why the Special Counsel did not subpoena President Trump, Mueller stated that they did not subpoena the president "because of the necessity of expediting" the investigation. "If we did subpoena the president, he would fight the subpoena and we would be in the midst of the investigation for a substantial period of time."<ref>{{Cite web |first=Zachary |last=Basu |date=July 24, 2019 |url=https://www.axios.com/robert-mueller-house-intelligence-testimony-russia-investigation-99ea7e11-6d6d-431c-aa3f-18ff103b9478.html|title=5 big moments from Mueller's House Intelligence testimony|website=Axios|language=en|access-date=July 28, 2019}}</ref>

=== Senate Intelligence Committee ===
The [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence|Senate Intelligence Committee]] had no doubts about Trump and his campaign's efforts to help Russia:
{{blockquote|
(U) The Committee's bipartisan Report unambiguously shows that members of the Trump Campaign cooperated with Russian efforts to get Trump elected. It recounts efforts by Trump and his team to obtain dirt on their opponent from operatives acting on behalf of the Russian government. It reveals the extraordinary lengths by which Trump and his associates actively sought to enable the Russian interference operation by amplifying its electoral impact and rewarding its perpetrators - even after being warned of its Russian origins. And it presents, for the first time, concerning evidence that the head of the Trump Campaign was directly connected to the Russian meddling through his communications with an individual found to be a Russian intelligence officer.

(U) These are stubborn facts that cannot be ignored. They build on the Committee's bipartisan findings in Volume 2 and Volume 4 that show an extensive Kremlin-directed effort to covertly help candidate Trump in 2016, and they speak to a willingness by a major party candidate and his associates, in the face of a foreign adversary's assault on the political integrity of the United States, to welcome that foreign threat in exchange for advancing their own self-interest.<ref name="SICv5_8/18/2020">{{cite web | publisher=[[Senate Intelligence Committee report on Russian interference in the 2016 United States presidential election|Senate Intelligence Committee]] (SIC) | date=August 18, 2020 | title=Volume 5: Counterintelligence Threats and Vulnerabilities | website=intelligence.senate.gov | url=https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/report_volume5.pdf | access-date=December 27, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210122003727/https://www.intelligence.senate.gov/sites/default/files/documents/report_volume5.pdf | archive-date=January 22, 2021 | url-status=live}}</ref>{{rp|943}}}}

== Possible future releases ==
A less-redacted version of the report "with all redactions removed except those relating to grand-jury information", which is required to be redacted by federal law,<ref name="redaction" /><ref name="LII6e" /><ref name="FASoversight" /> is expected{{update inline|date=November 2020|reason=It's been longer than that now, hasn't it?}} to be available two weeks after the initial public release, to "a bipartisan group of leaders from several Congressional committees".<ref name="PramukCNBC20190418" /><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/17/politics/redacted-mueller-report-congress/index.html |date=April 18, 2019 |title= Justice Dept. to release two versions of redacted Mueller report |first= Katelyn |last= Polantz |website=[[CNN]] |access-date= April 18, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://apnews.com/a99d0b66de82494bb29ca16ec8443643 |title= The Latest: Top lawmakers will see less redacted report |date= April 18, 2019 |website=[[Associated Press]] |access-date= April 18, 2019 }}</ref>

On April 19, 2019, [[United States House Committee on the Judiciary|House Judiciary Committee]] chairman [[Jerry Nadler]] issued a [[subpoena]] for the fully unredacted report.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/house-judiciary-chairman-nadler-subpoenas-full-unredacted-mueller-report-n996291 |title= House Judiciary Chairman Nadler subpoenas full, unredacted Mueller report |website=[[NBC News]] |date=April 19, 2019 |first=Rebecca |last=Shabad |access-date=April 24, 2019 }}</ref> A DOJ spokesperson called Nadler's subpoena "premature and unnecessary", citing that the publicly released version of the report had "minimal redactions" and that Barr had already made arrangements for Nadler and other lawmakers to review a version with fewer redactions.<ref name=":12" /><ref name=":13" /> Barr offered to let twelve designated members of Congress view the less-redacted report in a secure room at the Justice Department, and forbade them from sharing the contents with other legislators. Several Republicans took advantage of the offer; the six Democrats refused, saying the conditions were too stringent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/04/30/mueller-report-redacted-1295105 |title=Just 2 lawmakers have seen less-redacted Mueller report |last1=Cheney |first1=Kyle |last2=Levine |first2=Marianne |date=April 30, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=May 9, 2019 |archive-date=May 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509012051/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/04/30/mueller-report-redacted-1295105 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On May 8, 2019, President Trump used a "protective assertion" of [[executive privilege]] to block the subpoena by the House of Representatives. Thus, {{As of|2019|5|8|lc=y}}, the House would not receive the unredacted Mueller Report and its underlying material, pending Trump's decision to make a "final assertion" of executive privilege after reviewing the subpoenaed material. Attorney General Barr had recommended earlier that day that Trump take this action.<ref name=protectiveass>{{cite web |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |title=Trump asserts 'executive privilege' over Mueller report in fight with House Democrats |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/08/trump-will-assert-executive-privilege-over-mueller-report-materials.html |date=May 8, 2019 |website=[[CNBC]] |access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref>

=== Review of redactions ===
In March 2020, federal judge [[Reggie Walton]], appointed to his position by President [[George W. Bush]], declared that he would personally review the redactions made in the Mueller report to ensure that the redactions were legitimate. This came during a lawsuit filed by the pro-transparency [[Electronic Privacy Information Center]] and media outlet ''[[BuzzFeed News]]'' to release the full, unredacted report under the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Polantz |first1=Katelyn |title=Federal judge blasts William Barr for Mueller report rollout, asks if it was meant to help Trump |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/05/politics/judge-mueller-report-barr/index.html |access-date=March 7, 2020 |work=[[CNN]] |date=March 7, 2020 |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307002718/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/05/politics/judge-mueller-report-barr/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=March 22, 2019|title=Electronic Privacy Information Center V. United States Department Of Justice - docket files|url=https://www.courtlistener.com/docket/14782332/electronic-privacy-information-center-v-united-states-department-of/|access-date=June 19, 2020|website=Court Listener}}</ref> Walton cited that he had concerns on whether the redactions were legitimate, due to Attorney General William Barr having displayed a "lack of candor" regarding the report.

[[File:Muller_Report_Vol._1_—_Comparison_with_June_2020_Roger_Stone_Unredactions.pdf|thumb|A comparison of the originally-released Muller Report and the one released in June 2020 with sections regarding Roger Stone revealed.]]

According to Walton, Barr's March 24 letter not only had a "hurried release", but also "distorted" the findings of the report; while Barr went on to make "misleading public statements" about the report. As such, Walton had concerns that Barr may have made a "calculated attempt to influence public discourse" in favor of President Trump by establishing "a one-sided narrative" about the report which was contrary to the report's findings. Walton questioned if the report's redactions were then in fact "self-serving" to avoid conflict with Barr's statements, and if the Justice Department used "[[wikt:post hoc|post-hoc]] rationalizations" to defend Barr.<ref name="SavageMarch">{{cite news |last1=Savage |first1=Charlie |title=Judge Calls Barr's Handling of Mueller Report 'Distorted' and 'Misleading' |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/mueller-report-barr-judge-walton.html |access-date=March 7, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200305235542/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/mueller-report-barr-judge-walton.html |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="SternMarch">{{cite news | author-link = Mark Joseph Stern | last1 = Stern  |first1=Mark Joseph |title=Federal Judge Says He Needs to Review Every Mueller Report Redaction Because Barr Can't Be Trusted |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2020/03/barr-mueller-report-redactions-foia.html |access-date=March 7, 2020 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> On June 19, 2020, in response to the lawsuit, the Department of Justice released a less-redacted public version of the Mueller report, revealing new information about [[Roger Stone]] and [[WikiLeaks]]. The unredacted portions contradicted public statements made by Trump and the campaign officials that they did not know anything about the WikiLeaks release beforehand, and this information was corroborated by the [[Senate Intelligence Committee report on Russian interference in the 2016 United States presidential election]] that was released in August 2020.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Ken |last=Dilanian |title=Six revelations in Senate intel report on 2016 Russian interference|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/five-revelations-senate-intel-report-2016-russian-interference-n1237184 |access-date=2021-02-02 |website=NBC News |date=August 19, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Leopold |first1=Jason |author1-link=Jason Leopold |last2=Cormier |first2=Anthony |last3=Bensinger |first3=Ken |date=June 19, 2020 |title=Roger Stone Told Trump In Advance Wikileaks Would Release Documents Harmful To Clinton Campaign, Aides Claimed |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/jasonleopold/roger-stone-warned-trump-wikileaks-clinton-dump |access-date=June 19, 2020 |website=BuzzFeed News}}</ref>

On October 6, 2020 President Trump, referencing the Mueller report, tweeted "I have fully authorized the total Declassification of any & all documents pertaining to the single greatest political CRIME in American History, the [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections#Trump claims it's all a "hoax"|Russia Hoax]]."<ref name=MSNtweets/> Trump also said in an interview "I've fully declassified everything. Everything's been declassified."<ref name=MSNtweets/> In response to the President's statement, BuzzFeed requested an unredacted version of the report; however, BuzzFeed's request for an unredacted report was denied by the Department of Justice (DOJ).  Someone told Walton, "... the President's statements on Twitter were not self-executing declassification orders..." To clear up the position of the President, Walton ordered a continuance until October 21, 2020, so "I can get something from White House counsel saying that they conferred with the president, and the president, in fact, did not intend to declassify the information ..."<ref name=MSNtweets>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/judge-orders-doj-to-find-out-if-trump-s-declassification-tweets-mean-entire-mueller-report-should-be-released/ar-BB1a6zDv |via=[[MSN]] |work=[[Washington Examiner]] |title=Judge orders DOJ to find out if Trump's declassification tweets mean entire Mueller report should be released |date=October 16, 2020 |access-date=November 11, 2020 |first=Jerry |last=Dunleavy }}</ref> On October 20, 2020, and contrary to Trump's Twitter statements, White House chief of staff [[Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)|Mark Meadows]] stated in a federal court filing that Trump's tweets were not official orders to declassify FBI Russia probe documents.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/10/20/mark-meadows-trump-didnt-declassify-russia-docs-in-tweets/ |work=[[New York Post]] |title=Mark Meadows: Trump didn't declassify Russia docs in tweets |first=Steven |last=Nelson |date=October 20, 2020 |access-date=November 11, 2020}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=November 2020}}

The day before the November 3, 2020, election, the Special Counsel's office released previously redacted portions of the Mueller report per the federal judge's order in the lawsuit mentioned above filed by ''BuzzFeed News'' and the Electronic Privacy Information Center, while allowing other portions to remain redacted.<ref name="Buzz1102">{{Cite web|last1=Leopold|first1=Jason|author1-link=Jason Leopold|last2=Bensinger|first2=Ken|title=New: Mueller Investigated Julian Assange, WikiLeaks, And Roger Stone For DNC Hacks|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/jasonleopold/new-mueller-investigated-julian-assange-wikileaks-and-roger|date=November 3, 2020|access-date=November 3, 2020|website=[[BuzzFeed News]]|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last1=Leopold|first1=Jason|author1-link=Jason Leopold|last2=Bensinger|first2=Ken|title=A Judge Has Ordered The Justice Department To Release More Portions Of The Mueller Report Before Election Day|url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/jasonleopold/judge-orders-more-mueller-report-unredacted|date=September 30, 2020|access-date=November 3, 2020|website=[[BuzzFeed News]]|language=en}}</ref>

In summary, per Buzzfeed: "Although Wikileaks published emails stolen from the DNC in July and October 2016 and Stone{{snd}}a close associate to Donald Trump{{snd}}appeared to know in advance the materials were coming, investigators 'did not have sufficient evidence' to prove active participation in the hacks or knowledge that the electronic thefts were continuing. In addition, federal prosecutors could not establish that the hacked emails amounted to campaign contributions benefitting Trump's election chances …"<ref name="Buzz1102" />

The newly released material also stated: "While the investigation developed evidence that the GRU's hacking efforts in fact were continuing at least at the time of the July 2016 WikiLeaks dissemination, ... the Office did not develop sufficient admissible evidence that WikiLeaks knew of{{snd}}or even was willfully blind to{{snd}}that fact." As reported by Buzzfeed, "Likewise, prosecutors faced what they called factual hurdles in pursuing Stone for the hack."<ref name="Buzz1102" />

