== Synopsis ==
=== Setting ===
''My Hero Academia'' is set in a world where about 80% of the human population has gained [[Superpower (ability)|superpowers]] called {{nihongo4|"Quirks"|個性|Kosei}} as a result of [[recent human evolution]]. Quirks vary widely and have the possibility of being genetically inherited, with the series' focal Quirk "One for All" being the only one that can be passed on without heritage. Most Quirks are generally small in scale, but some exhibit near god-like ability. Almost every Quirk has some sort of physical drawback, whether it be a usage limit or self-injury. Some Quirks also cause physical [[mutation]]s to a person's body. Known as {{Nihongo|Mutants|異形|Igyō}}, people with these Quirks face [[discrimination]] and are given the [[pejorative]] "heteromorphs". The 20% of the population without Quirks, known as "Quirkless", also tend to get this treatment, albeit less severely. Quirks will generally manifest in an individual just after their toddler years. 

As Quirks became dominant among the population, society melded around their existence and largely [[Commodification|commodified]] around them. Although the first case of a Quirk was in [[China]], in the following years [[Japan]] emerged as the country with by far the highest percentage of Quirk population and strength, using this influence to become a [[superpower]] country. Despite this, other countries such as the [[United States]] also have heavy Quirk populations and influence.

Among the Quirk-enhanced individuals, a few of them earn the title of [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Pro Heroes|Heroes]], who cooperate with authorities in rescue operations and apprehending criminals who abuse their Quirks, commonly known as [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Villains|Villains]]. Heroes work out of Hero Agencies, which serves as their base of operations and a means for them to operate a business from their heroics. There are two different kinds of Hero Agency structures: one in which there is a single Hero owning the agency who also employs lower-level heroes called [[Sidekick]]s, and another in which a group of heroes will own an agency together as a [[List of superhero teams and groups|team]]. In addition, Heroes who excel in their duties gain celebrity status and are recognized as {{nihongo4|"Pro Heroes"|プロヒーロー|Puro Hīrō}}. Heroes are ranked in popularity via the Hero [[Billboard Charts]], with higher ranking heroes receiving public appeal, although it is not uncommon for novice heroes to gain popularity as well. 

Pro Heroes begin their initial training in high school, of which U.A. High School in [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], Japan is considered by far the most prestigious. In addition to regular schooling, students are taught different forms of hero training such as combat and rescue operations, as well as how to meld their individual skills and overcome their drawbacks. Companies will also sponsor the students, mainly by constructing, repairing, and remodeling superhero suits for them. They also take part in events to show their skills to the public, such as [[Sports Day (Japan)|sports festivals]] and [[Cultural festival (Japan)|cultural festivals]]. These events also serve as a way for Pro Heroes to scout students to intern for them. While initially forbidden from heroic work, students will eventually partake in the Provisional Hero License Exam, which gives them a temporary amateur Hero License before they become fully registered.

There are two types of [[internships]] that offer the opportunity to become a Pro Hero. The first type is the Hero Agency Internship in which the Pro Heroes can send a request to students that wish to work under them, such as in the aftermath of the Sports Festival. It involves a student shadowing a Pro Hero, listening to their advice, and watching them in action for a week. The second type is the Hero Work-Study, where, after a student acquires a Hero License, they can apply to function as real sidekicks. This also allows them to gain experience and can help them get noticed by other Pro Heroes who might hire them as full-time sidekicks once they graduate.

Initially the people who volunteered to do their heroic duties without permission were recognized as {{nihongo4|"Vigilantes"|ヴィジランテ|Vijirante}}. Students who have acted as vigilantes are not allowed to work as heroes due to Quirk restriction laws managed by the {{nihongo|Hero Public Safety Commission|ヒーロー公安委員会|Hīrō Kōan Iinkai}}. While the act of vigilantism is inherently illegal, the vigilantes themselves represent a moral [[wikt:grey area|gray area]]. The Hero Public Safety Commission originally enlisted vigilantes to do their dirty work until they became too organized for the vigilantes to properly deal with, so they abandoned the idea and instead focused on recruiting Pro Heroes. Some vigilantes wear costumes, but since they do not have access to support companies like heroes do, they are made out of regular clothes and everyday items.

=== Plot ===
{{Main|List of My Hero Academia characters{{!}}List of ''My Hero Academia'' characters}}
[[Izuku Midoriya|Izuku "Deku" Midoriya]] is a Quirkless boy who, despite his lack of powers, dreams of becoming a [[Superhero|Hero]] and attending U.A. High School, idolizing Japan's No. 1 Hero, [[All Might]] who also attended U.A. He is frequently picked on by others for this, particularly his childhood friend [[Katsuki Bakugo]]. One day, however, Deku attempts to save Bakugo from a villain, which is witnessed by All Might himself. Inspired by his natural heroism, the formerly Quirkless All Might chooses him to inherit his Quirk "One For All"—which gives him the ability to stockpile his raw power and pass it on to others—and become his successor. All Might was severely injured by his arch-nemesis [[All For One (My Hero Academia)|All For One]], whose Quirk allows him to steal other Quirks for his use and pass them over to others at his will, hastening the need for a successor. After nearly a year of physical training, Deku inherits One For All and passes the entrance exam to U.A. by saving [[Ochaco Uraraka]]. Deku, Uraraka, and Bakugo are among the twenty students placed in [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Class 1-A students|Class 1-A]], where Deku's tenacity earns him several friends.

During one of their classes, Class 1-A encounters the [[List of My Hero Academia characters#League of Villains|League of Villains]], led by All For One's apprentice [[Tomura Shigaraki]]. Shigaraki attempts to use an artificial being called a Nomu, which can stockpile different Quirks together, to kill All Might, but All Might overpowers the Nomu. Afterwards, Class 1-A takes part in a sports festival with the rest of their grade, where Deku comes into conflict with [[Shoto Todoroki]], the son of the No. 2 Hero [[Enji Todoroki|Endeavor]] who mistreated him and his family for years, leading Todoroki to resent him. As the festival progresses, Deku helps Todoroki accept his past and move on without resentment. As Bakugo wins the festival, 1-A's Class Representative [[Tenya Ida]]'s older brother is crippled by [[Stain (My Hero Academia)|Stain]], a villain who believes most heroes only desire fame. 

The class goes on there Hero Agency internships, with Deku interning with [[Gran Torino (My Hero Academia)|Gran Torino]], a former mentor of All Might's. During the internship, Ida finds Stain and attempts to get revenge. Though Ida is dispatched, Stain is ultimately defeated by Deku and Todoroki. Despite this, Stain's ideology spreads, and many of his believers join the League of Villains, including [[Dabi (My Hero Academia)|Dabi]], [[Himiko Toga]], and [[Twice (My Hero Academia)|Twice]]. After the class finishes final exams, the League of Villains' recruits ambush Classes 1-A and [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Class 1-B students|1-B]] while they are training at a summer camp, and kidnap Bakugo in the hopes of recruiting him. All Might leads several heroes in locating the League of Villains' hideout, where All For One reveals himself. Deku and some of his friends rescue Bakugo as All Might battles All For One. All For One is defeated and imprisoned, but All Might exhausts the last of One For All's power and retires. Endeavor, now the No. 1 Hero, is humbled by this added responsibility and begins trying to make amends with his family. 

The class partakes in their Provisional Hero License Exam, which Todoroki and Bakugo fail and leads to them needing to take remedial courses. In the aftermath, Bakugo deduces the secret of One For All but agrees to keep it hidden. Afterwards, Class 1-A meets with the "[[List of My Hero Academia characters#The Big 3|Big Three]]", U.A. High School's top-ranked seniors who select a few Class 1-A students to join them as interns; one of the Big Three, [[Mirio Togata]] selects Deku for an internship with All Might's former sidekick [[Sir Nighteye]]. Deku learns that Mirio was initially intended to be the next successor of One For All; despite this, Mirio takes a liking to Deku. Nighteye's team comes into conflict with the [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Shie Hassaikai|Shie Hassaikai]], a [[yakuza]] group allied with the League of Villains who are experimenting on their boss's granddaughter [[Eri (My Hero Academia)|Eri]] to synthesize a drug that suppresses Quirks. Nighteye leads his agency, alongside those of the other Big Three, in a raid Shie Hassaikai's facility to save Eri, during which Nighteye is killed and Mirio is de-powered. Eri is taken in by the U.A. staff, and Class 1-A performs a rock concert for her during the school cultural festival.

During a battle exercise with Class 1-B, Deku begins to awaken all of the Quirks used by the [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Past Users of One for All|previous users of One For All]]. He eventually continues his internship with Endeavor, alongside Bakugo and Todoroki. Meanwhile, the League of Villains defeats and merges with another villain group, the [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Meta Liberation Army|Meta Liberation Army]] who seek Quirk equality, forming the Paranormal Liberation Front with Shigaraki as their commander. A war ensues where the pro and training heroes attempt to defeat the Paranormal Liberation Front; Twice is killed by the number two hero [[Hawks (My Hero Academia)|Hawks]], but most of the remaining top members escape, including Shigaraki, who now inherits All For One's Quirk and is possessed by him. Mirio is re-powered by Eri, and joins the heroes partway through the war. Uraraka develops sympathy for Toga after the latter interrogates her about Twice's death. Dabi reveals himself as the presumed-dead son of Endeavor, whose abuse led him to villainy, with in combination with the rampant destruction the heroes failed to stop shatters the public's trust in heroes. 

Thousands of imprisoned Villains break out, including the original All For One, causing Japan to descend into chaos. Believing his classmates are no longer be safe with the world knowing about One For All, Deku leaves U.A. to hunt for All For One with Japan's top heroes, using himself as bait in the process. However, this leads Deku to physical ruin, and All For One sends jaded former Hero [[Kaina Tsutsumi|Lady Nagant]] after him. After Deku defeats and makes amends with Nagant, Deku's classmates intervene and bring him back to U.A., which is now a refugee camp. Civilians protest Deku's return until Uraraka pleads to them that heroes need protection too.

After Deku recovers, Class 1-A student [[Yuga Aoyama]] is discovered to be a double agent for All For One and the one responsible for the first two League of Villains attacks. After reconciling with his class, the Heroes uses Aoyama's connection to lure the Paranormal Liberation Front into a trap that scatters them across the country for the remaining members to be defeated by the heroes. Toga transforms into Twice using a combination of her Quirk and Twice's blood and nearly kills Uraraka, but the two girls come to an understanding and Toga dies saving Uraraka's life. The Todoroki family subdues Dabi after preventing his suicidal final attack. All For One attempts to reach Shigaraki's location and is stalled by many heroes, including All Might using a [[powered exoskeleton]], as well as a reformed Nagant and Stain (the latter of whom is killed by All for One) before his original body is eventually killed by Bakugo. Shigaraki battles Deku and breaks free from All For One's control. Unable to defeat him physically, Deku forcefully transfers One For All to Shigaraki to damage him from within. All For One regains control, but is defeated by hero reinforcements; as the remnants of the past One For All wielders and Shigaraki rebel against him, Deku strikes the killing blow on both All For One and Shigaraki.

Eight years later, Deku has lost the power of One For All completely and is a hero course teacher at U.A., while his former classmates work as pro heroes or sidekicks. All Might gives Deku a powered suit of his own, funded by his former classmates, which he uses to return to hero work while continuing to teach at U.A. In the following months, Deku enters a relationship with Uraraka and becomes the No. 4 Hero.

== Production ==
=== Development ===
Writer Kōhei Horikoshi stated that after his previous series ''[[Barrage (manga)|Barrage]]'' was canceled after just two volumes, he was depressed and out of ideas.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:「ヒーローのかっこよさは、戦闘じゃなくて人を救うこと」 『僕のヒーローアカデミア』堀越耕平インタビュー|url=https://ddnavi.com/news/226937/a/|website=Da Vinci News|date=February 20, 2015|access-date=April 5, 2021|language=ja|archive-date=December 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201205093352/https://ddnavi.com/news/226937/a/|url-status=live}}</ref> To formulate more ideas, he revisited a [[One-shot (comics)|one-shot]] he previously published in ''[[Akamaru Jump]]'', titled {{Nihongo|''My Hero''|僕のヒーロー|Boku no Hīrō}}. This would end up being the basis for ''My Hero Academia''.<ref name="mangaplus">{{Cite web|title='Until Jump Comics Is Brought to the Shelves!' — My Hero Academia|url=https://mangaplus.shueisha.co.jp/web_pages/126/|department=Project : Interviewing editors at manga+ (vol.1)|work=[[Manga Plus]]|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|access-date=July 5, 2019|archive-date=May 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190512105544/https://mangaplus.shueisha.co.jp/web_pages/126/|url-status=live}}</ref> Horikoshi was also an avid fan of American films and comics, such as [[Sam Raimi]]'s ''[[Spider-Man (2002 film)|Spider-Man]]'' trilogy, ''[[Star Wars]]'', and ''[[X-Men]]'', which he used for inspiration.<ref name="horikoshiANN">{{Cite web|last=Aoki|first=Deb|title=Interview: My Hero Academia Creator Kohei Horikoshi|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2018-08-24/interview-my-hero-academia-creator-kohei-horikoshi/.135449|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 24, 2018|access-date=April 5, 2021|archive-date=February 26, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210226052050/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2018-08-24/interview-my-hero-academia-creator-kohei-horikoshi/.135449|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="mangaplus"/> Horikoshi cites [[Masashi Kishimoto]]'s ''[[Naruto]]'' manga series as being the main influence for his art, specifically stating it gave him a love for drawing hands.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:一番最初にガツンときたのは鬼兄弟！【対談】岸本斉史×堀越耕平|url=https://ddnavi.com/news/233992/a/?doing_wp_cron=1439813760.0952670574188232421875|website=Da Vinci News|date=April 8, 2015|access-date=April 5, 2021|language=ja|archive-date=December 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201185706/https://ddnavi.com/news/233992/a/?doing_wp_cron=1439813760.0952670574188232421875|url-status=live}}</ref> Horikoshi has also cited ''[[Dragon Ball]]'', ''[[Ultraman]]'', and ''[[Kamen Rider]]'' as sources of inspiration.<ref name="horikoshiANN"/><ref name="mangaplus"/> Additionally, Horikoshi noted that he is a fan of the [[kaiju]] franchises ''[[Gamera]]'' and ''[[Godzilla]]'' and has mentioned and made reference to them in several comments.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:堀越耕平『僕のヒーローアカデミア』インタビュー 師弟関係の描写はあの映画からの影響大!! そして今後の展開でデクたちの“アレ”が変わる……!?|url=https://konomanga.jp/interview/67220-2|website=[[Kono Manga ga Sugoi!]]|date=June 19, 2016|access-date=February 28, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=September 25, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230925103723/https://konomanga.jp/interview/67220-2|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:ヒーローアカデミア堀越耕平先生ジャンプ巻末コメント一覧|url=https://sagisi4.sakura.ne.jp/haguruma/ha/ha07.html|website=Sakura Internet|access-date=February 28, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=February 28, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240228135035/https://sagisi4.sakura.ne.jp/haguruma/ha/ha07.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Hitoshi Koike, the editor of ''My Hero Academia'', said that Horikoshi already had a general story in mind for the manga. However, he also noted there were many rejected story ideas, and that Horikoshi dismissed some ideas himself. Koike also stated that Horikoshi liked to use his inspirations.<ref name="mangaplus"/> Koike additionally noted ''My Hero Academia''{{'}}s first three chapters took longer to complete than many other new serialized works. Koike and Horikoshi worked on character design concepts while finishing the storyboards; Koike felt excited about the characters' designs despite not knowing their role in the plot.<ref name="mangaplus"/>

Kengo Monji, the second editor of the manga, said Horikoshi had a difficult time writing chapters at first. Monji felt that the manga was mixing the flair of Japan's [[Shōnen manga|{{Transliteration|ja|shōnen}} manga]] with "heroes", a concept that he thought was understandable to a wide audience. Monji also complimented Horikoshi's artwork, noting its [[cartoon]]-style.<ref name="mangaplus"/>

=== Conclusion ===
Horikoshi originally stated that ''My Hero Academia'' would not be as long as ''[[One Piece]]'' since he felt he did not have enough stamina; he instead preferred to keep it concise in comparison to other {{Transliteration|ja|shōnen}} manga series.<ref name="horikoshiANN"/> In April 2021, Horikoshi stated that the series had continued for longer than expected, but that it was still leading toward the ending that he had decided upon before the series began.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=Kōhei Horikoshi Confirms My Hero Academia Manga Still Heading Toward His Planned Ending|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-04-30/kohei-horikoshi-confirms-my-hero-academia-manga-still-heading-toward-his-planned-ending/.172271|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 30, 2021|access-date=May 1, 2021|archive-date=January 11, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111022510/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-04-30/kohei-horikoshi-confirms-my-hero-academia-manga-still-heading-toward-his-planned-ending/.172271|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2021, he stated during an interview at [[Jump Festa|Jump Festa '22]] that "if things go smoothly, the manga will meet its goal to end in one year. If it doesn't go smoothly, I think [Izuku's voice actor] Yamashita will be reading out the exact same letter from me at next year's Jump Festa." He also teased that [[Katsuki Bakugo]] would soon get a "big scene".<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Kohei Horikoshi: 'If Things Go Smoothly My Hero Academia Will Meet Its Goal in 1 Year'|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-12-19/kohei-horikoshi-if-things-go-smoothly-my-hero-academia-will-meet-its-goal-in-1-year/.180767|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 19, 2021|access-date=December 20, 2021|archive-date=January 29, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220129040626/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-12-19/kohei-horikoshi-if-things-go-smoothly-my-hero-academia-will-meet-its-goal-in-1-year/.180767|url-status=live}}</ref> Horikoshi wrote in the 34th volume of the manga that "I feel like I can finally see the goal in sight. It's a rather strange feeling getting to this point. In the past, I would just be drawing without a single care [for the future], but now I wonder just how many more times can I draw these characters? Change is scary as you grow older. Well, I really shouldn't dwell on that! Until next volume then!".<ref>{{Cite web|last=Valdez|first=Nick|title=My Hero Academia Creator Shares Sober Message About the Series' End|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/news/my-hero-academia-manga-ending-goal-kohei-horikoshi-message/|website=[[ComicBook.com]]|date=May 2, 2022|access-date=September 9, 2022|archive-date=July 23, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220723151235/https://comicbook.com/anime/news/my-hero-academia-manga-ending-goal-kohei-horikoshi-message/|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2022, the author rescinded the statement he made during Jump Festa '22, opting to take longer to complete the manga's final arc than initially expected.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cacciatore|first=Francesco|title=My Hero Academia Isn't as Close to Ending as Fans Think, Creator Confirms|url=https://screenrant.com/my-hero-academia-ending-not-close-horikoshi-postponed/|website=[[Screen Rant]]|date=October 15, 2022|access-date=December 2, 2022|archive-date=November 12, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221112070030/https://screenrant.com/my-hero-academia-ending-not-close-horikoshi-postponed/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In December 2022, although Horikoshi stated that his estimations were wrong, he said that the ending of the manga is "very close".<ref>{{Cite web|last=Madillo|first=A.R.|title=My Hero Academia Manga's Ending Is 'Very Close', Horikoshi Says At Jump Festa 2023|url=https://animehunch.com/my-hero-academia-mangas-ending-is-very-close-horikoshi-says-at-jump-festa-2023/|website=Animehunch|date=December 17, 2022|access-date=March 31, 2024|archive-date=January 27, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230127070515/https://animehunch.com/my-hero-academia-mangas-ending-is-very-close-horikoshi-says-at-jump-festa-2023/|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2023, he reiterated on what he said in the previous year's event. However, he added that there were still many things he wanted to draw beyond the battle that was currently ongoing in the manga. The author also jokingly said that "if the series continues until next year's Jump Festa, we will hold a Dogeza Festival on the stage."<ref>{{Cite web|last=Madillo|first=A.R.|title=Will Do Dogeza On Stage If MHA Continues Till Next Jump Festa, Says Kohei Horikoshi|url=https://animehunch.com/will-do-dogeza-on-stage-if-mha-continues-till-next-jump-festa-says-kohei-horikoshi/|website=Animehunch|date=December 16, 2023|access-date=March 31, 2024|archive-date=March 31, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240331111506/https://animehunch.com/will-do-dogeza-on-stage-if-mha-continues-till-next-jump-festa-says-kohei-horikoshi/|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2024, [[Shueisha]] announced in the year's 27th issue of ''[[Weekly Shōnen Jump]]'' that the manga had entered its "epilogue" with the 424th chapter. Horikoshi stated in his comment that although the conclusion of a story is usually short, it is not the kind of manga to end immediately after defeating the villain, and so it will go on "a little longer," and he added that the manga would "return to its title."<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Enters 'Epilogue;' Author States Manga Will Continue for 'A While' as it 'Returns to its Title' (Updated)|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-06-03/my-hero-academia-enters-epilogue-author-states-manga-will-continue-for-a-while-as-it-returns-to-its-/.211432|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 3, 2024|access-date=June 7, 2024|archive-date=June 7, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240607010422/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-06-03/my-hero-academia-enters-epilogue-author-states-manga-will-continue-for-a-while-as-it-returns-to-its-/.211432|url-status=live}}</ref> Later in the same month, it was announced that the series would end in five chapters after a ten-year run on August 5, 2024. The author expressed gratitude to his fans that made it possible for him to draw [[Izuku Midoriya|Deku]] and the others for the past ten years.<ref name="manga-ending"/>

=== Anime adaptation ===
''My Hero Academia'' producer Wakana Okamura, who previously worked with animation studio [[Bones (studio)|Bones]] on ''[[Blood Blockade Battlefront]]'', stated in an interview that he chose to work with Bones on adapting the series because he felt they would make it a "high-quality production" with a "wide reach [both] internationally and domestically". Okamura also stated the production staff, especially character designer [[Yoshihiko Umakoshi]], were fans of the manga.<ref name="productionref1">{{Cite web|last=Chapman|first=Jacob|title=Interview: The Cast and Crew of My Hero Academia|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-07-27/interview-the-cast-and-crew-of-my-hero-academia/.104588|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 27, 2016|access-date=April 21, 2023|archive-date=December 25, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221225053150/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-07-27/interview-the-cast-and-crew-of-my-hero-academia/.104588|url-status=live}}</ref> Director [[Kenji Nagasaki]] said Bones wanted to "make [the series] with a strong core and backbones".<ref name="productionref1"/> [[Yōsuke Kuroda]] said he was a fan of the series prior to its anime adaptation, so he quickly accepted when offered to do the screenwriting.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Valentine|first=Evan|title=My Hero Academia Writer Addresses the Secret to the Anime's Success|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/news/my-hero-academia-writer-anime-success/|website=[[ComicBook.com]]|date=April 6, 2023|access-date=April 21, 2023|archive-date=April 8, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230408173417/https://comicbook.com/anime/news/my-hero-academia-writer-anime-success/|url-status=live}}</ref>

For the casting, ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' magazine announced that the anime would be starring [[Daiki Yamashita]] as Izuku Midoriya, [[Kenta Miyake]] as All Might, [[Nobuhiko Okamoto]] as Katsuki Bakugo, [[Ayane Sakura]] as Ochaco Uraraka, [[Kaito Ishikawa]] as Tenya Iida, [[Aoi Yūki]] as Tsuyu Asui, [[Ryō Hirohashi]] as Minoru Mineta, [[Marina Inoue]] as Momo Yaoyorozu, and [[Yoshimasa Hosoya]] as Fumikage Tokoyami.<ref name="cast">{{Cite web|last=Blyden|first=Jabulani|title=Marina Inoue, Yoshimasa Hosoya Join My Hero Academia Anime's Cast|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-01-28/marina-inoue-yoshimasa-hosoya-join-my-hero-academia-anime-cast/.98062|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 28, 2016|access-date=February 1, 2020|archive-date=February 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201202048/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-01-28/marina-inoue-yoshimasa-hosoya-join-my-hero-academia-anime-cast/.98062|url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2016, [[Tasuku Hatanaka]], [[Toshiki Masuda]] and [[Yuki Kaji]] joined the cast as Denki Kaminari, Eijirō Kirishima and [[Shoto Todoroki|Shōto Todoroki]], respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=My Hero Academia Anime Casts Yuuki Kaji as Shōto Todoroki|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-02-10/my-hero-academia-anime-casts-yuuki-kaji-as-shoto-todoroki/.98527|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 10, 2016|access-date=October 31, 2023|archive-date=September 29, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929161647/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-02-10/my-hero-academia-anime-casts-yuuki-kaji-as-shoto-todoroki/.98527|url-status=live}}</ref> In an interview with [[Justin Briner]] and [[Christopher Sabat]], they expressed interest about the English [[Dubbing|dub]] in [[Funimation]]. Briner, the voice of Izuku, said the dubbing process was more consistent, but also said it felt strange to do it on a regular home video release. Sabat, who voices All Might, felt that even the actors and director were continuing the show without knowing the full story because they had not yet been told what the story was.<ref name="productionref1"/>

During the production for the anime's [[My Hero Academia season 2|second season]], Umakoshi was impressed by Horikoshi's designs, feeling they were very well-suited for animation. He also stated that in terms of giving the characters more life and movement, all they basically did was simplify the dialogue. He believed that the manga already had a lot of movement before animating. Regarding the fight between Todoroki and Izuku, Umakoshi believed that he was able to develop a story that could not fail by considering which part of the story would be handled by which key animation, and by choosing someone with a high level of skill. He identified certain things and collated who would work best in other parts of the scene. After the airing of an episode, Umakoshi felt that the anime had a great response not only from fans of the manga but also from regular Japanese viewers.<ref name="productionref2">{{Cite web|last=Chapman|first=Jacob|title=Interview: My Hero Academia's Yoshihiko Umakoshi and Chris Sabat|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2017-08-07/interview-my-hero-academia-yoshihiko-umakoshi-and-chris-sabat/.119811|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 7, 2017|access-date=October 31, 2023|archive-date=June 24, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230624111900/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2017-08-07/interview-my-hero-academia-yoshihiko-umakoshi-and-chris-sabat/.119811|url-status=live}}</ref>

Umakoshi was also looking forward not only the development of the relationship between Deku and All Might, but also between Deku and Bakugo in the future material of the manga, which had not been animated yet. Unlike the other ''Shonen Jump'' adaptation titles such as ''[[Naruto (TV series)|Naruto]]'' and ''[[One Piece (1999 TV series)|One Piece]]'', where the staff worked throughout the year, Umakoshi said the production cycle of ''My Hero Academia'' is split into batches. He also said: "Personally, it would be best if I could be working on it continuously, throughout a whole year. But in reality, sometimes it doesn't work out that way, due to different aspects of business and things. But in reality, the schedule did line up so that we worked on the second season right after the first season ended, so I have been working on it somewhat continuously, even if the delivery of the product comes in batches."<ref name="productionref2"/>

=== Themes and analysis ===
Horikoshi has stated that the main theme he focuses on is "what makes a hero".<ref name="Natalie">{{Cite web|script-title=ja:堀越耕平インタビュー|url=https://natalie.mu/comic/pp/heroaca|website=[[Comic Natalie]]|publisher=Natasha, Inc|date=July 4, 2018|access-date=April 5, 2021|language=ja|archive-date=November 17, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201117103535/https://natalie.mu/comic/pp/heroaca|url-status=live}}</ref> He also stated that he likes stories with bad endings, as well as horror stories. However, he finds these difficult to draw since the mood in his stories is based on his own current mood. To combat this, he adds in more silly-looking characters such as [[Taishiro Toyomitsu|Fat Gum]], in order to keep the mood up.<ref name="Natalie"/>

The series explores themes such as the nature of heroism, the importance of perseverance and determination, and the [[power of friendship]] and teamwork. Horikoshi said that he was inspired by the idea of creating a world where anyone, regardless of their background or abilities, could become a hero. He wanted to show that even those without powers could still make a difference and achieve their dreams through hard work and determination.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Kōhei Horikoshi: The Mastermind Behind the Phenomenal Success of My Hero Academia|url=https://mangaka.info/kohei-horikoshi/|website=Mangaka.info|access-date=February 29, 2024|archive-date=September 30, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230930100129/https://mangaka.info/kohei-horikoshi/|url-status=dead}}</ref> That vision results in heroes in the series not being egotistical, but passionate and dedicated individuals with clear goals to work towards.<ref name="heroicspirit">{{Cite web|last=Creamer|first=Nick|title=The Heroic Spirit of My Hero Academia|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-05-20/the-heroic-spirit-of-my-hero-academia/.101961|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 20, 2016|access-date=April 21, 2023|archive-date=November 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201114235556/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2016-05-20/the-heroic-spirit-of-my-hero-academia/.101961|url-status=live}}</ref> The series also explores Izuku's idolization of heroes from a young age and his enthusiasm. In a world where superheroes are not just regulated, but commercialized brands, he still sees something inspiring in their actions.<ref name="heroicspirit"/>

''My Hero Academia'' has been noted for its positive view of heroes. Cramer wrote that "in the modern world, we often challenge heroic ideals, and the motivations of the people who pursue them", noting how in American media, the optimism of the [[Silver Age of Comic Books]] lead to post-''[[Watchmen]]'' ambiguity. He also noted that, even in Japan, unquestioned heroism is often challenged in modern revisions of older series, such as in ''[[Yatterman]]'' and ''[[Gatchaman (OVA)|Gatchaman]]''.<ref name="heroicspirit"/>

== Media ==
=== Manga ===
{{Main|List of My Hero Academia chapters{{!}}List of ''My Hero Academia'' chapters}}
Written and illustrated by [[Kōhei Horikoshi]], ''My Hero Academia'' began its serialization in [[Shueisha]]'s [[Shōnen manga|{{Transliteration|ja|shōnen}} manga]] magazine ''[[Weekly Shōnen Jump]]'' on July 7, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=Shonen Jump to Launch 4 Manga Series in Next 3 Issues|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-06-25/shonen-jump-to-launch-4-manga-series-in-next-3-issues/.75929|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 25, 2014|access-date=November 30, 2014|archive-date=December 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205060040/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-06-25/shonen-jump-to-launch-4-manga-series-in-next-3-issues/.75929|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:堀越耕平、ヒーロー夢見る少年描く新連載始動|url=https://natalie.mu/comic/news/120645|website=[[Comic Natalie]]|publisher=Natasha, Inc|date=July 7, 2014|access-date=August 4, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=January 22, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240122031912/https://natalie.mu/comic/news/120645|url-status=live}}</p></ref> The series ended after a ten-year run on August 5, 2024.<ref name="manga-ending">{{Cite web|script-title=ja:「僕のヒーローアカデミア」残り5話で完結！最終回は8月5日発売のジャンプに掲載|url=https://natalie.mu/comic/news/579188|website=[[Comic Natalie]]|publisher=Natasha, Inc|date=June 24, 2024|access-date=June 24, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=June 24, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240624130849/https://natalie.mu/comic/news/579188|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Cayanan|first=Joanna|title=My Hero Academia Manga to End in 5 Chapters|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-06-24/my-hero-academia-manga-to-end-in-5-chapters/.212355|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 24, 2024|access-date=June 24, 2024|archive-date=June 24, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240624130850/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-06-24/my-hero-academia-manga-to-end-in-5-chapters/.212355|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:「僕のヒーローアカデミア」完結！ファンブックと初の画集発売、原画展開催が決定|url=https://natalie.mu/comic/news/585104|website=[[Comic Natalie]]|publisher=Natasha, Inc|date=August 5, 2024|access-date=August 4, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=August 4, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240804153049/https://natalie.mu/comic/news/585104|url-status=live}}</p></ref> Its chapters were collected and published by Shueisha into 42 individual {{Transliteration|ja|[[tankōbon]]}} volumes, released from November 4, 2014, to December 4, 2024;<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア 1|url=https://books.shueisha.co.jp/items/contents.html?isbn=978-4-08-880264-0|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|access-date=January 4, 2021|language=ja|archive-date=December 2, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201202101159/https://books.shueisha.co.jp/items/contents.html?isbn=978-4-08-880264-0|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア 42|url=https://www.shueisha.co.jp/books/items/contents.html?isbn=978-4-08-884349-0|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|access-date=November 6, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=November 6, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241106073715/https://www.shueisha.co.jp/books/items/contents.html?isbn=978-4-08-884349-0|url-status=live}}</p></ref> the final volume includes 38 pages of new content that take place after the original ending.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=My Hero Academia Manga's Final Volume Adds 38 Pages of New Content Following Original Ending|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-11-21/my-hero-academia-manga-final-volume-adds-38-pages-of-new-content-following-original-ending/.218141|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 21, 2024|access-date=December 26, 2024|archive-date=December 2, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241202215924/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-11-21/my-hero-academia-manga-final-volume-adds-38-pages-of-new-content-following-original-ending/.218141|url-status=live}}</ref>

The series is licensed for English-language release in North America by [[Viz Media]], which published the first volume on August 4, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|title=My Hero Academia, Vol. 1|url=https://www.viz.com/read/manga/my-hero-academia-volume-1/product/3767|publisher=[[Viz Media]]|access-date=March 30, 2015|archive-date=September 24, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200924142116/https://www.viz.com/read/manga/my-hero-academia-volume-1/product/3767|url-status=live}}</ref> As the series was published in Japan, it was also released simultaneously in English digitally by Viz Media's ''[[Weekly Shonen Jump (American magazine)|Weekly Shonen Jump]]'' and later its website.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ressler|first=Karen|title=Viz's Shonen Jump Adds My Hero Academia|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-26/viz-shonen-jump-adds-my-hero-academia/.83716|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 26, 2015|access-date=January 26, 2015|archive-date=January 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128225340/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-26/viz-shonen-jump-adds-my-hero-academia/.83716|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="S2Anc">{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 2nd Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-06-23/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-2nd-season/.103534|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 23, 2016|access-date=June 23, 2016|archive-date=June 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160623233238/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-06-23/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-2nd-season/.103534|url-status=live}}</ref> Shueisha began to simulpublish the series in English on the website and ''[[Manga Plus]]'' app in January 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Morrissy|first=Kim|title=Everything You Need to Know about MANGA Plus by Shueisha|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2019-01-27/everything-you-need-to-know-about-manga-plus-by-shueisha/.142401|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 27, 2019|access-date=January 5, 2021|archive-date=January 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129201611/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/feature/2019-01-27/everything-you-need-to-know-about-manga-plus-by-shueisha/.142401|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Spin-offs ====
{{Main|My Hero Academia: Smash!!{{!}}''My Hero Academia: Smash!!''|My Hero Academia: Vigilantes{{!}}''My Hero Academia: Vigilantes''|My Hero Academia: Team-Up Missions{{!}}''My Hero Academia: Team-Up Missions''}}
Three spin-off manga series have also been released. The first, ''[[My Hero Academia: Smash!!]]'' by Hirofumi Neda, is a comedy manga which ran in the ''[[Shōnen Jump+]]'' digital app from November 9, 2015, to November 6, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Gets Spinoff Manga, 'Important Announcement' Next Week|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-10-22/my-hero-academia-gets-spinoff-manga-important-announcement-next-week/.94499|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 22, 2015|access-date=March 17, 2019|archive-date=February 14, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214124436/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-10-22/my-hero-academia-gets-spinoff-manga-important-announcement-next-week/.94499|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MHA-anime-and-spinoff">{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia TV Anime Adaptation Confirmed|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-10-29/my-hero-academia-tv-anime-adaptation-confirmed/.94768|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 29, 2015|access-date=March 17, 2019|archive-date=May 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508220109/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-10-29/my-hero-academia-tv-anime-adaptation-confirmed/.94768|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:『僕のヒーローアカデミア すまっしゅ!!』次回で最終回！配信は11月6日＆リクエストお題箱を実施|url=https://heroaca.net/archives/104|website=heroaca.net|date=October 3, 2017|access-date=March 17, 2019|language=ja|archive-date=April 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404201830/https://heroaca.net/archives/104|url-status=live}}</ref> Its chapters were collected in five {{Transliteration|ja|tankōbon}} volumes.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ressler|first=Karen|title=My Hero Academia Smash Spinoff Manga to End With 5th Volume in November|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-09-19/my-hero-academia-smash-spinoff-manga-to-end-with-5th-volume-in-november/.121572|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=March 17, 2019|archive-date=March 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190311062650/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-09-19/my-hero-academia-smash-spinoff-manga-to-end-with-5th-volume-in-november/.121572|url-status=live}}</ref> The second spin-off manga, ''[[My Hero Academia: Vigilantes]]'', is a prequel to the main series written by Hideyuki Furuhashi and illustrated by Betten Court, which ran from August 20, 2016, to May 28, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ressler|first=Karen|title=My Hero Academia Gets 'Vigilante' Spinoff Manga|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-07-19/my-hero-academia-gets-vigilante-spinoff-manga/.104358|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 19, 2016|access-date=October 14, 2020|archive-date=July 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721034609/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-07-19/my-hero-academia-gets-vigilante-spinoff-manga/.104358|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:ヴィジランテ-僕のヒーローアカデミアILLEGALS-|url=https://www.shonenjump.com/j/rensai/list/vigilante.html|website=[[Weekly Shōnen Jump]]|date=November 17, 2015|access-date=May 5, 2018|language=ja|archive-date=July 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708155740/https://www.shonenjump.com/j/rensai/list/vigilante.html|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia: Vigilantes Spinoff Manga Ends in Next Chapter on May 28|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-05-13/my-hero-academia-vigilantes-spinoff-manga-ends-in-next-chapter-on-may-28/.185661|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 13, 2022|access-date=May 27, 2022|archive-date=May 27, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220527170748/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-05-13/my-hero-academia-vigilantes-spinoff-manga-ends-in-next-chapter-on-may-28/.185661|url-status=live}}</p></ref> Its chapters were collected in 15 {{Transliteration|ja|tankōbon}} volumes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shueisha.co.jp/books/items/contents.html?isbn=978-4-08-883177-0|script-title=ja:ヴィジランテ 15―僕のヒーローアカデミアILLEGALS―|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|access-date=July 6, 2022|language=ja|archive-date=May 19, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220519141805/https://www.shueisha.co.jp/books/items/contents.html?isbn=978-4-08-883177-0|url-status=live}}</ref> The third spin-off manga, ''[[My Hero Academia: Team-Up Missions]]'' by Yōkō Akiyama, features various side stories. It began serialization in ''[[Saikyō Jump]]'' on August 2, 2019, with a prologue chapter debuting in ''Jump GIGA'' on July 25, 2019;<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Gets New Spinoff Manga This Month|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-12/my-hero-academia-gets-new-spinoff-manga-this-month/.148950|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 13, 2019|access-date=July 13, 2019|archive-date=July 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190713000011/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-12/my-hero-academia-gets-new-spinoff-manga-this-month/.148950|url-status=live}}</ref> the series ended on January 4, 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cayanan|first=Joanna|title=My Hero Academia: Team-Up Missions Spinoff Manga Listed to End Next Week|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-12-25/my-hero-academia-team-up-missions-spinoff-manga-listed-to-end-next-week/.219490|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 25, 2024|access-date=December 26, 2024|archive-date=December 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241226102157/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-12-25/my-hero-academia-team-up-missions-spinoff-manga-listed-to-end-next-week/.219490|url-status=live}}</ref> The three spin-off manga were licensed for the English-language release in North America by Viz Media.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Sherman|first=Jennifer|title=Viz Media Licenses My Hero Academia: Smash!!, Komi Can't Communicate, Beastars Manga|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-17/viz-media-licenses-my-hero-academia-smash-komi-cant-communicate-beastars-manga/.139608|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 17, 2018|access-date=April 2, 2021|archive-date=November 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181117235646/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-17/viz-media-licenses-my-hero-academia-smash-komi-cant-communicate-beastars-manga/.139608|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=Viz Media Licenses That Blue Sky Feeling Manga for Summer 2018 Release|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-11-17/viz-media-licenses-that-blue-sky-feeling-manga-for-summer-2018-release/.124155|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 17, 2017|access-date=March 19, 2021|archive-date=January 13, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210113092548/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-11-17/viz-media-licenses-that-blue-sky-feeling-manga-for-summer-2018-release/.124155|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|last=Sherman|first=Jennifer|title=Viz Media's Shonen Jump Adds My Hero Academia: Team-Up Missions, Jujutsu Kaisen 0, Naruto: Shikamaru's Story—Mourning Clouds|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-07-03/viz-media-shonen-jump-adds-my-hero-academia-team-up-missions-jujutsu-kaisen-0-naruto-shikamaru-story-mourning-clouds/.161407|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 3, 2020|access-date=August 10, 2020|archive-date=August 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200806135730/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-07-03/viz-media-shonen-jump-adds-my-hero-academia-team-up-missions-jujutsu-kaisen-0-naruto-shikamaru-story-mourning-clouds/.161407|url-status=live}}</p></ref>

The four series' films have been adapted into one-volume manga series by Homesha.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3278-3/|script-title=ja:劇場版アニメコミックス「僕のヒーローアカデミア ＴＨＥ ＭＯＶＩＥ ～２人の英雄～」|title=Gekijō-ban Anime Komikkusu "Boku no Hīrō Akademia Za Mūbī Futari no Eiyū"|publisher=Homesha|access-date=September 16, 2023|language=ja|archive-date=February 20, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230220093942/https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3278-3/|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3293-6/|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア THE MOVIE HEROES：RISING ーヒーローズ：ライジングー アニメコミックス|title=Boku no Hīrō Akademia Za Mūbī Hīrōzu: Raijingu Anime Komikkusu|publisher=Homesha|access-date=September 16, 2023|language=ja|archive-date=October 20, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211020134850/https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3293-6/|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3310-0/|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア THE MOVIE WORLD HEROES' MISSION アニメコミックス|title=Boku no Hīrō Akademia Za Mūbī Wārudo Hīrōzu Misshon Anime Komikkusu|publisher=Homesha|access-date=September 16, 2023|language=ja|archive-date=July 7, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707062809/https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3310-0/|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|url=https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3341-4/|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア THE MOVIE YOU'RE NEXT アニメコミックス|title=Boku no Hīrō Akademia Za Mūbī Yuā Nekusuto Anime Komikkusu|publisher=Homesha|access-date=August 7, 2025|language=ja|archive-date=August 7, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250807134900/https://www.homesha.co.jp/products/items/isbn-978-4-8342-3341-4/|url-status=live}}</p></ref> A 15-page [[One-shot (comics)|one-shot]] spin-off manga, illustrated by Yōkō Akiyama, centered on [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Melissa Shield|Melissa]], titled {{Nihongo|''Everyone Is Surely Someone's Hero''|きっと誰もが誰かのヒーロー|Kitto Daremo ga Dareka no Hero}}, was published in the 35th issue of Shueisha's ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' on July 30, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=More Cast, Spinoff Manga 1-shot Revealed for My Hero Academia: Two Heroes Film|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-07-23/more-cast-spinoff-manga-1-shot-revealed-for-my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film/.134565|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 23, 2018|access-date=July 23, 2018|archive-date=September 17, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210917124353/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-07-23/more-cast-spinoff-manga-1-shot-revealed-for-my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film/.134565|url-status=live}}</ref> A one-shot spin-off manga that serves as a prequel to the [[My Hero Academia: Two Heroes|first film]], written and illustrated by Kōhei Horikoshi, centered on [[All Might]]'s past and the featured character [[Nana Shimura]], titled {{Nihongo|''No. 0 All Might: Rising''|No.0 オールマイト：ライジング|Nanbā 0 Ōru Maito: Raijingu}}, was given to the first one million attendees on August 3, 2018. A ten-page manga was included in the {{Nihongo|''My Hero Academia Two Heroes Vol. 0 Origin''|僕のヒーローアカデミア２人の英雄 Vol.0 Origin|Boku no Hīrō Akademia 2-ri no Eiyū Vol. 0 Origin}} book.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia: Two Heroes Film Offers 'Volume 0' Book to 1st Million Moviegoers in Japan (Updated)|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-06-17/my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-offers-volume-0-book-to-1st-million-moviegoers-in-japan/.133013|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 17, 2018|access-date=April 3, 2021|archive-date=November 27, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201127120038/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-06-17/my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-offers-volume-0-book-to-1st-million-moviegoers-in-japan/.133013|url-status=live}}</ref> It was later published in English by Viz Media in September 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Viz Media Releases My Hero Academia: Two Heroes Film's Bonus Manga in English|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-09-20/viz-media-releases-my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-bonus-manga-in-english/.137062|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 20, 2018|access-date=April 3, 2021|archive-date=March 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210316134915/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-09-20/viz-media-releases-my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-bonus-manga-in-english/.137062|url-status=live}}</ref>

{{Nihongo|''Deku & Bakugo: Rising''|出久&爆豪:ライジング|Deku Ando Bakugo: Raijingu}}, a two-chapter spin-off manga illustrated by Akiyama, was published in Shueisha's ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' on December 16 and 23, 2019. It centered on [[Izuku Midoriya]] and [[Katsuki Bakugo]] during their second year in middle school.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:「出久＆爆豪：ライジング」 あきやま陽光 ＞ 週刊少年ジャンプ読切！|url=https://mdb.way-nifty.com/bokunenjin/2019/12/post-834d6f.html|publisher=朴念仁と居候|date=December 13, 2019|access-date=June 19, 2020|language=ja|archive-date=September 22, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210922153131/https://mdb.way-nifty.com/bokunenjin/2019/12/post-834d6f.html|url-status=live}}</ref> A one-shot spin-off manga that serves as a prequel to the [[My Hero Academia: Heroes Rising|second film]], written and illustrated by Horikoshi, centered on [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Nine|Nine]], titled {{Nihongo|''League of Villains: Undercover''|ヴィランれんごう:アンダーカバー|Viran Rengō: Andākabā}}, was also given to the first million attendees on December 20, 2019. A nine-page manga was included in the {{Nihongo|''My Hero Academia Heroes: Rising Vol. R''|僕のヒーローアカデミア ヒーローズ：ライジング Vol.R|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Hīrōzu: Raijingu Vol. R}} book.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=My Hero Academia -Heroes: Rising- Filmgoers Get Manga Bonus|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-10-07/my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-filmgoers-get-manga-bonus/.151947|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 7, 2019|access-date=February 20, 2020|archive-date=June 4, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220604014338/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-10-07/my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-filmgoers-get-manga-bonus/.151947|url-status=live}}</ref> It was later published in English by Viz Media in March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Viz Media Publishes My Hero Academia: Heroes Rising Manga Chapter in English|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-27/viz-media-publishes-my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-manga-chapter-in-english/.158019|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 27, 2020|access-date=February 13, 2021|archive-date=April 9, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210409161208/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-03-27/viz-media-publishes-my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-manga-chapter-in-english/.158019|url-status=live}}</ref>

A 17-page special one-shot chapter written and illustrated by Akiyama, titled {{Nihongo|''My Hero Academia Tokubetsu Spinoff: Endeavor's Mission''|僕のヒーローアカデミア 特別スピンオフ エンデヴァーズ ミッション|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Tokubetsu Supin'ofu Endevāzu Misshon}}, was published in ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' on August 2, 2021. It centered on [[Enji Todoroki|Endeavor]] and his trainees Izuku, Katsuki, and [[Shoto Todoroki|Shoto]] during their Hero Work-Studies at the Endeavor Agency.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Promised Neverland Creators, My Hero Academia Each Get 1-Shot in Shonen Jump|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-07-18/promised-neverland-creators-my-hero-academia-each-get-1-shot-in-shonen-jump/.175240|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 18, 2021|access-date=August 11, 2021|archive-date=May 27, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220527224616/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-07-18/promised-neverland-creators-my-hero-academia-each-get-1-shot-in-shonen-jump/.175240|url-status=live}}</ref> An 80-page manga booklet, titled {{Nihongo|''My Hero Academia World Heroes' Mission Vol. W''|僕のヒーローアカデミア ワールドヒーローズミッション Vol. W|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Wārudo Hīrōzu Misshon Vol. W}}, includes a nine-page one-shot manga that serves as a prequel to the [[My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission|third film]], centered on Endeavor Agency trainees and the featured character [[Hawks (My Hero Academia)|Hawks]], titled {{Nihongo|''No. XXX Hawks: Soothe''|No.XXX ホークス:スーズ|Nanbā XXX Hōkusu: Sūzu}}<ref name="VolWH">{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia World Heroes' Mission Film's Theatergoers Get Manga Volume as Bonus (Updated)|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-06-13/my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-film-theatergoers-get-manga-volume-as-bonus/.173882|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 13, 2021|access-date=July 28, 2021|archive-date=May 2, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220502072602/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-06-13/my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-film-theatergoers-get-manga-volume-as-bonus/.173882|url-status=live}}</ref> was given to the ''My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission'' attendees who viewed the film in Japan on August 6, 2021. The manga volume had a limited print run of one million copies.<ref name="VolWH"/> In October 2021, a 76-page booklet featuring a specialty manga was also given to the attendees who saw it on the opening weekend in the United States.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=Unveils My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission Anime Film's English Dub Trailer, Manga Booklet for Theatergoers|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-10-01/funimation-unveils-my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-anime-film-english-dub-trailer-manga-/.178060|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 1, 2021|access-date=October 2, 2021|archive-date=July 8, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220708111111/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-10-01/funimation-unveils-my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-anime-film-english-dub-trailer-manga-/.178060|url-status=live}}</ref>

A 16-page one-shot spin-off chapter written and illustrated by Akiyama, titled ''Connect to the Day'', was published in ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' on July 29, 2024. It takes place before the Final War, centered on [[List of My Hero Academia characters#Class 1-A students|Class 1-A students]] during their mission to capture the Jailbreakers.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:ヒロアカ、あきやま陽光が描く劇場版につながる読切がジャンプに　本編は次号完結|url=https://natalie.mu/comic/news/584118|website=[[Comic Natalie]]|publisher=Natasha, Inc|date=July 29, 2024|access-date=October 1, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=September 10, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240910150949/https://natalie.mu/comic/news/584118|url-status=live}}</ref> An 80-page manga booklet, titled {{Nihongo|''My Hero Academia Vol. Next''|僕のヒーローアカデミア Vol. Next|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Vol. Nekusuto}}, includes a seven-page one-shot manga that serves as a prequel to the [[My Hero Academia: You're Next|fourth film]], centered on Class 1-A students, titled ''A Piece of Cake'', was given to the ''My Hero Academia: You're Next'' attendees who viewed the film in Japan on August 2, 2024. The manga volume had a limited print run of 1.5 million copies.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Tai|first=Anita|title=My Hero Academia: You're Next Film's Moviegoers Get Manga Volume Bonus|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-06-29/my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-moviegoers-get-manga-volume-bonus/.212624|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 29, 2024|access-date=June 30, 2024|archive-date=June 30, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240630072656/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-06-29/my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-moviegoers-get-manga-volume-bonus/.212624|url-status=live}}</ref> The manga chapter was later published in English by Viz Media in October 2024.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=Viz Publishes My Hero Academia: You're Next Film's 1-Shot Manga|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-10-08/viz-publishes-my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-1-shot-manga/.216479|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 8, 2024|access-date=October 8, 2024|archive-date=October 8, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241008231321/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-10-08/viz-publishes-my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-1-shot-manga/.216479|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Anime ===
{{See also|List of My Hero Academia episodes{{!}}List of ''My Hero Academia'' episodes}}
On October 29, 2015, the series' official website announced that the manga would receive an [[anime]] television series adaptation produced by [[Bones (studio)|Bones]].<ref name="MHA-anime-and-spinoff"/> The anime is directed by [[Kenji Nagasaki]], written by [[Yōsuke Kuroda]], and features character designs by [[Yoshihiko Umakoshi]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=My Hero Academia TV Anime's Main Staff Revealed|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-11-05/my-hero-academia-tv-anime-main-staff-revealed/.95027|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 5, 2015|access-date=November 5, 2015|archive-date=November 6, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106032819/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-11-05/my-hero-academia-tv-anime-main-staff-revealed/.95027|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="more staffs">{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 4th Promo Video Previews Animation|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-02-28/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-promo-video-previews-animation/.99186|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 28, 2016|access-date=February 28, 2016|archive-date=February 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160229211514/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-02-28/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-promo-video-previews-animation/.99186|url-status=live}}</ref> The series' first season aired from April 3 to June 26, 2016, on all [[Japan News Network|JNN]] affiliate stations, including [[TBS Television (Japan)|TBS]] and [[Mainichi Broadcasting System|MBS]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Blyden|first=Jabulani|title=My Hero Academia Anime to Air in MBS/TBS' 'Nichigo' Timeslot|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-01-10/my-hero-academia-anime-to-air-in-mbs-tbs-nichigo-timeslot/.97421|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 10, 2016|access-date=January 10, 2016|archive-date=January 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160111145624/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-01-10/my-hero-academia-anime-to-air-in-mbs-tbs-nichigo-timeslot/.97421|url-status=live}}</ref> A second season was announced in ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' magazine's 30th issue of 2016.<ref name="S2Anc"/> The season aired from April 1 to September 30, 2017, on all [[List of NNN and NNS affiliates|NNS]] affiliate stations, including [[Yomiuri Telecasting Corporation|YTV]] and [[Nippon Television|NTV]],<ref>{{Cite web|last=Yuan|first=Kevin|title=My Hero Academia Season 2 Anime to Air on NTV, YTV|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-12-22/my-hero-academia-season-2-anime-to-air-on-ntv-ytv/.110237|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 22, 2016|access-date=December 22, 2016|archive-date=December 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223015307/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2016-12-22/my-hero-academia-season-2-anime-to-air-on-ntv-ytv/.110237|url-status=live}}</ref> with the staff and cast from the first season reprising their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Green|first=Scott|title=Latest "My Hero Academia" Anime Cast Addition And Plans Spotted|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2017/02/02-1/latest-my-hero-academia-anime-cast-addition-and-plans-spotted|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=February 2, 2017|access-date=February 2, 2017|archive-date=February 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203081021/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2017/02/02-1/latest-my-hero-academia-anime-cast-addition-and-plans-spotted|url-status=live}}</ref> A third season was announced in the 44th issue of ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' magazine of 2017,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Green|first=Scott|title=My Hero Academia Season 3 Planned|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2017/09/29-1/my-hero-academia-anime-season-3-planned|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=September 29, 2017|access-date=September 29, 2017|archive-date=September 30, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930132426/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2017/09/29-1/my-hero-academia-anime-season-3-planned|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 3rd Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-09-30/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-3rd-season/.122039|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 30, 2017|access-date=October 2, 2017|archive-date=October 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002072018/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-09-30/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-3rd-season/.122039|url-status=live}}</p></ref> which aired from April 7 to September 29, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 3rd Season Premieres April 7|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2018-01-30/my-hero-academia-anime-3rd-season-premieres-april-7/.127106|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 30, 2018|access-date=April 2, 2021|archive-date=January 30, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130101946/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2018-01-30/my-hero-academia-anime-3rd-season-premieres-april-7/.127106|url-status=live}}</ref>

A fourth season was announced in the final episode of season three.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 4th Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-09-29/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-4th-season/.137465|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 29, 2018|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-date=September 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929160026/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-09-29/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-4th-season/.137465|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 19 of the same year, the series' official website confirmed a new key visual, along with its release date of October 12, 2019, which aired until April 4, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=My Hero Academia Season 4 Reveals October Premiere, 1st Visual|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2018-12-19/my-hero-academia-anime-season-4-reveals-october-premiere-1st-visual/.141015|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 19, 2018|access-date=December 19, 2018|archive-date=December 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219161850/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2018-12-19/my-hero-academia-anime-season-4-reveals-october-premiere-1st-visual/.141015|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|last=Osborn|first=Alex|title=My Hero Academia: Season 4 of Anime to premiere in October|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/12/19/my-hero-academia-season-4-of-anime-to-premiere-in-october|website=[[IGN]]|date=December 19, 2018|access-date=December 19, 2018|archive-date=December 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219201156/https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/12/19/my-hero-academia-season-4-of-anime-to-premiere-in-october|url-status=live}}</p></ref> [[Funimation]] premiered the first episode of the fourth season at [[Anime Expo]] on July 6, 2019 with the English [[Dubbing|dub]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=Anime Expo to Host My Hero Academia Season 4 Premiere|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-06-14/anime-expo-to-host-my-hero-academia-season-4-premiere/.147871|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 14, 2019|access-date=June 18, 2019|archive-date=June 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617170319/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-06-14/anime-expo-to-host-my-hero-academia-season-4-premiere/.147871|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=Funimation Reveals My Hero Academia Season 4's English-Dubbed Trailer|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-19/funimation-reveals-my-hero-academia-season-4-english-dubbed-trailer/.149135|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 19, 2019|access-date=September 6, 2019|archive-date=July 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719141533/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-19/funimation-reveals-my-hero-academia-season-4-english-dubbed-trailer/.149135|url-status=live}}</p></ref> Kenji Nagasaki served as chief director of the fourth season, with [[Masahiro Mukai]] as director.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 4th Season Reveals Promo Video, More Cast, October 12 Debut|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-06-16/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-season-reveals-promo-video-more-cast-october-12-debut/.147890|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 16, 2019|access-date=June 16, 2019|archive-date=June 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616135445/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-06-16/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-season-reveals-promo-video-more-cast-october-12-debut/.147890|url-status=live}}</ref> A fifth season was announced at the end of the final episode of season four,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 5th Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-04-04/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-5th-season/.158250|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 4, 2020|access-date=April 4, 2020|archive-date=April 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404091641/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-04-04/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-5th-season/.158250|url-status=live}}</ref> which aired from March 27 to September 25, 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 5th Season's New Promo Video Reveals March 27 Premiere|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-12-19/my-hero-academia-anime-5th-season-new-promo-video-reveals-march-27-premiere/.167618|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 19, 2020|access-date=December 19, 2020|archive-date=December 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201219075312/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-12-19/my-hero-academia-anime-5th-season-new-promo-video-reveals-march-27-premiere/.167618|url-status=live}}</ref>

A sixth season was announced at the end of the fifth season's final episode.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 6th Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-09-25/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-6th-season/.177815|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 25, 2021|access-date=September 25, 2021|archive-date=September 25, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210925103901/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-09-25/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-6th-season/.177815|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 24, 2022, the Hero Fes event confirmed a new visual, as well as its release date of October 1, 2022,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 6th Season Premieres on October 1|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-07-24/my-hero-academia-anime-6th-season-premieres-on-october-1/.187960|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 24, 2022|access-date=July 24, 2022|archive-date=July 24, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220724113428/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-07-24/my-hero-academia-anime-6th-season-premieres-on-october-1/.187960|url-status=live}}</ref> which ran for two consecutive [[Cours (TV production)|cours]] that aired until March 25, 2023; it adapted the manga's "Paranormal Liberation War" and "Dark Hero" [[story arc]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 6th Season to Air for Half a Year|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-09-24/my-hero-academia-anime-6th-season-to-air-for-half-a-year/.190115|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 24, 2022|access-date=September 24, 2022|archive-date=September 24, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220924131252/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-09-24/my-hero-academia-anime-6th-season-to-air-for-half-a-year/.190115|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia 6th Season Anime's 5th Promo Video Previews 'Black Hero Arc'|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-02-04/my-hero-academia-6th-season-anime-5th-promo-video-previews-black-hero-arc/.194530|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 4, 2023|access-date=March 25, 2023|archive-date=February 17, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230217141306/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-02-04/my-hero-academia-6th-season-anime-5th-promo-video-previews-black-hero-arc/.194530|url-status=live}}</p></ref> A seventh season was announced at the end of the sixth season's final episode,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 7th Season With Romi Park|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-03-25/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-7th-season-with-romi-park/.196424|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 25, 2023|access-date=March 25, 2023|archive-date=March 25, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230325102919/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-03-25/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-7th-season-with-romi-park/.196424|url-status=live}}</ref> which aired from May 4 to October 12, 2024, with four "Memories" recap specials having aired in the preceding month of April.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Airs 4-Episode Recap in April Before Premiering Season 7 on May 4|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-12-16/my-hero-academia-anime-airs-4-episode-recap-in-april-before-premiering-season-7-on-may-4/.205558|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 16, 2023|access-date=December 16, 2023|archive-date=December 16, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231216094414/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-12-16/my-hero-academia-anime-airs-4-episode-recap-in-april-before-premiering-season-7-on-may-4/.205558|url-status=live}}</ref> Naomi Nakayama served as the director of the seventh season.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア：テレビアニメ第7期が2024年5月4日スタート 新規シーン含む特別版「Memories」4月放送 劇場版第4弾は来夏公開|url=https://mantan-web.jp/article/20231216dog00m200011000c.html|website=[[Mantan Web]]|date=December 16, 2023|access-date=December 17, 2023|language=ja|archive-date=December 17, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231217015011/https://mantan-web.jp/article/20231216dog00m200011000c.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

An eighth and final season was announced at the end of the seventh season's final episode.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 'Final Season' in 2025|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-10-12/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-final-season-in-2025/.216660|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 12, 2024|access-date=October 12, 2024|archive-date=November 6, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241106073900/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-10-12/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-final-season-in-2025/.216660|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2025, Kōhei Horikoshi was confirmed to being heavily involved in the production, and would provide the new original scenes that were not included in the manga.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Valentine|first=Evan|title=My Hero Academia Creator Confirms New Scenes For Final Season (Exclusive)|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/news/my-hero-academia-final-season-new-scenes-exclusive/|website=[[ComicBook.com]]|date=July 5, 2025|access-date=October 4, 2025|archive-date=September 20, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250920160826/https://comicbook.com/anime/news/my-hero-academia-final-season-new-scenes-exclusive/|url-status=live}}</ref> The season premiered on October 4, 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cayanan|first=Joanna|title=My Hero Academia Anime's Final Season Premieres on October 4|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-07-15/my-hero-academia-anime-final-season-premieres-on-october-4/.226684|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 15, 2025|access-date=July 15, 2025|archive-date=July 15, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250715115006/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-07-15/my-hero-academia-anime-final-season-premieres-on-october-4/.226684|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Original video animations ====
{{See also|List of My Hero Academia episodes#OVAs{{!}}List of ''My Hero Academia'' episodes § OVAs}}
An [[original video animation]] (OVA) based on the anime series was shown at the [[Jump Festa|Jump Festa '16]] event on November 27, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=My Hero Academia's New Event Anime Special Previewed in Video|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-09-04/my-hero-academia-new-event-anime-special-previewed-in-video/.106095|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 4, 2016|access-date=September 4, 2016|archive-date=December 26, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221226141156/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-09-04/my-hero-academia-new-event-anime-special-previewed-in-video/.106095|url-status=live}}</ref> Titled "Save! Rescue Training!", it was bundled with the limited edition of the 13th volume of the manga, which released on April 4, 2017. It was later released on DVD releases alongside ''[[Black Clover]]'' and ''[[Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma]]'' bundled with the future volumes of their respective manga, as it was announced on Jump Special Anime Festa event.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia, Black Clover, Food Wars! Event Anime Get DVD Releases|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-12-01/my-hero-academia-black-clover-food-wars-event-anime-get-dvd-releases/.109366|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 1, 2016|access-date=December 6, 2020|archive-date=June 21, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621123437/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-12-01/my-hero-academia-black-clover-food-wars-event-anime-get-dvd-releases/.109366|url-status=live}}</ref> A second OVA, titled "Training of the Dead," bundled with a limited edition of the 14th volume of the manga, released on June 2, 2017. It focuses on a joint practice session between [[Izuku Midoriya|Izuku]]'s class and the other hero department students at U.A. Academy.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=My Hero Academia Manga Gets Original Anime in 14th Volume|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-22/my-hero-academia-manga-gets-original-anime-in-14th-volume/.111276|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 22, 2017|access-date=April 2, 2021|archive-date=November 11, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111223234/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-01-22/my-hero-academia-manga-gets-original-anime-in-14th-volume/.111276|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Ressler|first=Karen|title=My Hero Academia OVA Reveals Color Character Designs|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2017-02-27/my-hero-academia-ova-reveals-color-character-designs/.112773|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 27, 2017|access-date=March 1, 2017|archive-date=May 31, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220531232226/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2017-02-27/my-hero-academia-ova-reveals-color-character-designs/.112773|url-status=live}}</ref> A third OVA, "All Might: Rising," was released on February 13, 2019. It was bundled with the first film's [[Blu-ray]] set, and adapted its prequel manga.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=My Hero Academia: Two Heroes Film's Bonus 'All Might: Rising' Manga Gets Animated|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-18/my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-bonus-all-might-rising-manga-gets-animated/.139666|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 18, 2018|access-date=November 19, 2018|archive-date=June 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612055741/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-11-18/my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-bonus-all-might-rising-manga-gets-animated/.139666|url-status=live}}</ref> It was two minutes long.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Peters|first=Megan|title='My Hero Academia' Releases 'All Might Rising' OVA|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/2019/02/13/my-hero-academia-all-might-rising-anime-released-ova/|website=[[ComicBook.com]]|date=February 13, 2019|access-date=February 17, 2019|archive-date=March 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323084222/https://comicbook.com/anime/2019/02/13/my-hero-academia-all-might-rising-anime-released-ova/|url-status=live}}</ref>

A two-part [[original net animation]] (ONA) titled "Make It! Do-or-Die Survival Training," were released on August 16, 2020, with the returning staff and cast from season 4.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Gets New Original Anime Episode Streaming on August 16|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-08-02/my-hero-academia-gets-new-original-anime-episode-streaming-on-august-16/.162485|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 2, 2020|access-date=August 5, 2020|archive-date=September 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200930223046/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-08-02/my-hero-academia-gets-new-original-anime-episode-streaming-on-august-16/.162485|url-status=live}}</ref> Funimation streamed them simultaneously with the Japanese release.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=Funimation Streams 2-Part My Hero Academia Original Video Anime on August 15|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-08-02/funimation-streams-2-part-my-hero-academia-original-video-anime-on-august-15/.162501|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 2, 2020|access-date=June 20, 2022|archive-date=June 20, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220620043948/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-08-02/funimation-streams-2-part-my-hero-academia-original-video-anime-on-august-15/.162501|url-status=live}}</ref> An OVA based on the bonus manga chapter "Departure" was included with the "Plus Ultra" edition of ''My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission'' in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Harding|first=Daryl|title=''My Hero Academia World Heroes' Mission'' Japanese Blu-ray to Come With "No.XXX Hawks: SOOTHE" OVA|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2021/12/05-1/my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-japanese-blu-ray-to-come-with-noxxx-hawks-soothe-ova|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=December 6, 2021|access-date=January 2, 2022|archive-date=January 2, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220102142352/https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2021/12/05-1/my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-japanese-blu-ray-to-come-with-noxxx-hawks-soothe-ova|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new OVA episodes, titled "HLB <Hero League Baseball>" and "Laugh! As If You Are in Hell," were given screenings in Japan from June 16–19, 2022. Internationally, Crunchyroll premiered the episodes at Anime Expo on July 1, 2022. A worldwide streaming release premiered on August 1, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Gets Original 2-Episode Anime This Summer|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-05-08/my-hero-academia-gets-original-2-episode-anime-this-summer/.185411|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 8, 2022|access-date=June 20, 2022|archive-date=June 20, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220620042950/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-05-08/my-hero-academia-gets-original-2-episode-anime-this-summer/.185411|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=Crunchyroll to Stream My Hero Academia Anime's New OVA Episodes on August 1|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2022-07-01/crunchyroll-to-stream-my-hero-academia-anime-new-ova-episodes-on-august-1/.187280|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 1, 2022|access-date=July 5, 2022|archive-date=July 5, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220705191815/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/daily-briefs/2022-07-01/crunchyroll-to-stream-my-hero-academia-anime-new-ova-episodes-on-august-1/.187280|url-status=live}}</ref>

A special OVA episode, titled "UA Heroes Battle," premiered with an English dub at the [[New York Comic Con]] on October 13, 2023. The episode has given screenings in Japan from October 20–26, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Tai|first=Anita|title=My Hero Academia Gets New Anime Episode 'UA Heroes Battle' Next Month|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-09-18/my-hero-academia-gets-new-anime-episode-ua-heroes-battle-next-month/.202462|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 18, 2023|access-date=September 18, 2023|archive-date=September 18, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230918151930/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-09-18/my-hero-academia-gets-new-anime-episode-ua-heroes-battle-next-month/.202462|url-status=live}}</ref> Crunchyroll streamed it with English subtitles and dub on November 30 of the same year.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=Crunchyroll Announces True Beauty Anime, Streams Delusional Monthly Magazine, Senpai wa Otokonoko, More Anime|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-11-17/crunchyroll-announces-true-beauty-anime-streams-delusional-monthly-magazine-senpai-wa-otokonoko-/.204557|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 17, 2023|access-date=November 17, 2023|archive-date=November 17, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231117222158/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-11-17/crunchyroll-announces-true-beauty-anime-streams-delusional-monthly-magazine-senpai-wa-otokonoko-/.204557|url-status=live}}</ref> An OVA based on the bonus manga chapter "A Piece of Cake" was included with the deluxe "Plus Ultra" edition of ''My Hero Academia: You're Next'' in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=My Hero Academia You're Next Film's 'Plus Ultra' BD/DVD to Add New Anime Short|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-11-28/my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-plus-ultra-bd-dvd-to-add-new-anime-short/.218395|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 28, 2024|access-date=November 28, 2024|archive-date=November 28, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241128153526/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-11-28/my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-plus-ultra-bd-dvd-to-add-new-anime-short/.218395|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== International release ====
In March 2016, Funimation announced they had licensed the international rights for streaming services, the home and broadcast release, and the merchandise rights.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ressler|first=Karen|title=Funimation Licenses My Hero Academia Anime|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-08/funimation-licenses-my-hero-academia-anime/.99556|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 8, 2016|access-date=March 8, 2016|archive-date=March 10, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310154901/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-08/funimation-licenses-my-hero-academia-anime/.99556|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|title=Funimation Entertainment Acquires Exclusive International Rights to "My Hero Academia" from Toho|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2016-03-10/funimation-entertainment-acquires-exclusive-international-rights-to-my-hero-academia-from-toho/.99614|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 10, 2016|access-date=August 15, 2018|archive-date=August 15, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180815200733/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2016-03-10/funimation-entertainment-acquires-exclusive-international-rights-to-my-hero-academia-from-toho/.99614|url-status=live}}</p></ref> [[Universal Pictures UK]] distributed the first season in the United Kingdom and Ireland on behalf of Funimation,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Osmond|author-link=Andrew Osmond (journalist)|first=Andrew|title=BBFC Lists My Hero Academia From Universal|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-03-24/bbfc-lists-my-hero-academia-from-universal/.113866|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 24, 2017|access-date=March 24, 2017|archive-date=March 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325025958/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-03-24/bbfc-lists-my-hero-academia-from-universal/.113866|url-status=live}}</ref> with [[Sony Pictures UK]] distributing the second season for Funimation,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Rhodes|first=Dan|title=My Hero Academia Season 2, Part 1 UK release announced|url=http://www.uk-anime.net/newsitem/My_Hero_Academia_Season_2,_Part_1_UK_release_announced.html|website=UK Anime Network|date=March 9, 2018|access-date=May 10, 2018|archive-date=May 11, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511012947/http://www.uk-anime.net/newsitem/My_Hero_Academia_Season_2,_Part_1_UK_release_announced.html|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Crunchyroll UK and Ireland|Manga Entertainment]] distributing subsequent seasons for Funimation.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Stevens|first=Josh|title=My Hero Academia Season 3 Part 1 Listed by Retailers|url=https://animeuknews.net/2019/03/my-hero-academia-season-3-part-1-listed/|website=Anime UK News|date=March 15, 2019|access-date=March 21, 2019|archive-date=March 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331154311/https://animeuknews.net/2019/03/my-hero-academia-season-3-part-1-listed/|url-status=live}}</ref> In Australia and New Zealand, [[Universal Pictures Home Entertainment|Universal]] [[Sony Pictures Home Entertainment]] distributed the first two seasons, on behalf of Funimation,<ref>{{Cite web|title=My Hero Academia|url=https://theviewinglounge.com.au/view/my-hero-academia/|website=The Viewing Lounge|access-date=May 10, 2018|archive-date=September 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200907183919/http://theviewinglounge.com.au/view/my-hero-academia/|url-status=dead}}</ref> with [[Madman Anime]] distributing season 3 onwards, in partnership with Funimation.<ref>{{Cite web|title=My Hero Academia – Season 3 Part 1 DVD / Blu-Ray Combo|url=https://b2b.madman.com.au/actions/catalogue.do?method=view&releaseId=47430|publisher=[[Madman Entertainment]]|access-date=March 31, 2019|archive-date=May 2, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210502115612/https://b2b.madman.com.au/actions/catalogue.do?method=view&releaseId=47430|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 19, 2018, Funimation announced that the series would air on [[Adult Swim]]'s [[Toonami]] block starting on May 5, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ressler|first=Karen|title=My Hero Academia to Air on Toonami|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-04-19/my-hero-academia-to-air-on-toonami/.130595|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 19, 2018|access-date=April 19, 2018|archive-date=April 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419204831/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-04-19/my-hero-academia-to-air-on-toonami/.130595|url-status=live}}</ref> Medialink licensed the series in Southeast Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Medialink Group Limited Global Offering|url=https://www1.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/sehk/2019/0430/ltn20190430063.pdf|publisher=[[Medialink]]|date=April 30, 2019|access-date=April 2, 2021|archive-date=June 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616095006/https://www1.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/sehk/2019/0430/ltn20190430063.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> They aired it simultaneously on [[Animax (Asian TV channel)|Animax Asia]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=Exclusive: Animax Asia Airs Simulcast of My Hero Academia, Twin Star Exorcists|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-28/exclusive-animax-asia-airs-simulcast-of-my-hero-academia-twin-star-exorcists/.100379|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 28, 2016|access-date=April 6, 2016|archive-date=April 27, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427050413/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-28/exclusive-animax-asia-airs-simulcast-of-my-hero-academia-twin-star-exorcists/.100379|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2023, [[Cartoon Network (Indian TV channel)|Cartoon Network]] announced that the series would air in India starting on September 10, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hazra|first=Adriana|title=Cartoon Network Airs My Hero Academia Anime in India on September 10|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-08-25/cartoon-network-airs-my-hero-academia-anime-in-india-on-september-10/.201617|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 25, 2023|access-date=August 26, 2023|archive-date=August 26, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230826005810/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-08-25/cartoon-network-airs-my-hero-academia-anime-in-india-on-september-10/.201617|url-status=live}}</ref> The series began airing on [[AXS TV]] in the United States on February 20, 2025, as part of [[Web3]] company Azuki's Anime.com Hour programming block.<ref name="AXS-Anime"/>

==== Music ====
{{Main|Music of My Hero Academia{{!}}Music of ''My Hero Academia''}}
The original music of the series is composed by [[Yuki Hayashi (composer)|Yuki Hayashi]].<ref name="more staffs"/> The series has also used twenty-four different theme songs: twelve opening themes and twelve ending themes. The opening theme "The Day", performed by [[Porno Graffitti]], and the ending theme "Heroes", performed by [[Brian the Sun]], were used for the 13 episodes in the first season.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=Porno Graffiti, Brian the Sun Perform My Hero Academia Anime's Theme Songs|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-02-18/porno-graffiti-brian-the-sun-perform-my-hero-academia-anime-theme-songs/.98829|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 18, 2016|access-date=April 12, 2019|archive-date=April 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420121251/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-02-18/porno-graffiti-brian-the-sun-perform-my-hero-academia-anime-theme-songs/.98829|url-status=live}}</ref> For the second season, the first opening theme is {{nihongo|"[[Peace Sign (Kenshi Yonezu song)|Peace Sign]]"|ピースサイン}} performed by [[Kenshi Yonezu]] and the first ending theme is {{nihongo|"Dakara, Hitori ja nai"|だから、ひとりじゃない|Therefore, I am not Alone}} performed by [[Little Glee Monster]] for the first 13 episodes;<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=My Hero Academia Season 2's Ad Previews Opening Theme Song|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-03-31/my-hero-academia-season-2-ad-previews-opening-theme-song/.114158|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 31, 2017|access-date=March 3, 2018|archive-date=June 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170607214413/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-03-31/my-hero-academia-season-2-ad-previews-opening-theme-song/.114158|url-status=live}}</ref> from episode 14 onwards, the opening theme is {{nihongo|"Sora ni Utaeba"|空に歌えば|Singin' to the Sky}} performed by [[amazarashi]]<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Reveals New Opening Theme Artist, Cast for Gran Torino|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-22/my-hero-academia-anime-reveals-new-opening-theme-artist-cast-for-gran-torino/.117830|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 22, 2017|access-date=June 22, 2017|archive-date=June 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622114912/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-22/my-hero-academia-anime-reveals-new-opening-theme-artist-cast-for-gran-torino/.117830|url-status=live}}</ref> and the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Datte Atashi no Hīrō"|だってアタシのヒーロー|Still My Hero}} performed by [[Lisa (Japanese musician, born 1987)|LiSA]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=LiSA Performs New Ending Theme For My Hero Academia Anime's 2nd Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-18/lisa-performs-new-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime-2nd-season/.117638|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 18, 2017|access-date=March 3, 2018|archive-date=October 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171004181045/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-06-18/lisa-performs-new-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime-2nd-season/.117638|url-status=live}}</ref> For the first 13 episodes of the third season, the opening theme is "Odd Future" by [[Uverworld]], while the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Update"|アップデート}} by [[Miwa (singer)|miwa]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia 3rd Anime Season's 2nd Promo Video Previews UVERworld's Theme|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-03-03/my-hero-academia-3rd-anime-season-2nd-promo-video-previews-uverworld-theme/.128511|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 3, 2018|access-date=March 3, 2018|archive-date=March 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303225253/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-03-03/my-hero-academia-3rd-anime-season-2nd-promo-video-previews-uverworld-theme/.128511|url-status=live}}</ref> For the rest of the season, the opening theme is "Make my story" by Lenny code fiction and the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Long Hope Philia"|ロングホープ・フィリア}} by [[Masaki Suda]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Lenny code fiction, Masaki Suda Perform New Themes for My Hero Academia Anime's 3rd Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-06-24/lenny-code-fiction-masaki-suda-perform-new-themes-for-my-hero-academia-anime-3rd-season/.133333|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 24, 2018|access-date=June 24, 2018|archive-date=June 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180624234817/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-06-24/lenny-code-fiction-masaki-suda-perform-new-themes-for-my-hero-academia-anime-3rd-season/.133333|url-status=live}}</ref> For the first 14 episodes of the fourth season, the opening theme is {{nihongo|"Polaris"|ポラリス}} by Blue Encount, while the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Kōkai no Uta"|航海の唄|The Song of the Voyage}} by [[Sayuri (musician)|Sayuri]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Blue Encount, Sayuri Perform Theme Songs for My Hero Academia Anime's 4th Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-08-25/blue-encount-sayuri-perform-theme-songs-for-my-hero-academia-anime-4th-season/.150391|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 25, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019|archive-date=August 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825152953/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-08-25/blue-encount-sayuri-perform-theme-songs-for-my-hero-academia-anime-4th-season/.150391|url-status=live}}</ref> For the rest of the season, the opening theme is {{nihongo|"[[Starmarker]]"|スターマーカー}} by [[Kana-Boon]] and the ending theme is "Shout Baby" by [[Ryokuoushoku Shakai|Ryokuōshoku Shakai]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Sherman|first=Jennifer|title=KANA-BOON, Ryokuōshoku Shakai Perform My Hero Academia Anime's New Themes|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-01-03/kana-boon-ryokuoshoku-shakai-perform-my-hero-academia-anime-new-themes/.154895|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 3, 2020|access-date=January 3, 2020|archive-date=March 5, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305161422/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-01-03/kana-boon-ryokuoshoku-shakai-perform-my-hero-academia-anime-new-themes/.154895|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kyoka Jiro]] starring [[Chrissy Costanza]] performs the insert songs "Each Goal" in episode 19 and "Hero too" in episode 23, with the former insert song was uncredited, while the latter insert song was credited as the [[cultural festival (Japan)|U.A. School Festival]] track.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=ChrissyCostanza|author-link=Chrissy Costanza|last=Costanza|first=Chrissy|number=1241167355507597313|title=おはよう日本🤍 I hope you guys will be watching the new My Hero Academia today 😉😘|date=March 21, 2020|access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>

For the first 13 episodes of the fifth season, the opening theme is "No.1" by [[Dish (band)|Dish]], while the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Ashiato"|足跡||{{lit|Footprints}}}} by [[the Peggies]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 5th Season Previews Opening Theme in New Video|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-02-27/my-hero-academia-anime-5th-season-previews-opening-theme-in-new-video/.170037|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 27, 2021|access-date=February 27, 2021|archive-date=February 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227120726/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-02-27/my-hero-academia-anime-5th-season-previews-opening-theme-in-new-video/.170037|url-status=live}}</ref> From episode 14 onwards, the opening theme is "Merry-Go-Round" by [[Man with a Mission]], while the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Uso ja Nai"|嘘じゃない||{{lit|Not a Lie}}}} by Soshi Sakiyama.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Season 5 Anime Previews New 'Internship at Endeavor's Agency' Arc in Video|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-06-19/my-hero-academia-season-5-anime-previews-new-internship-at-endeavor-agency-arc-in-video/.174172|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 19, 2021|access-date=June 19, 2021|archive-date=June 19, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210619094106/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-06-19/my-hero-academia-season-5-anime-previews-new-internship-at-endeavor-agency-arc-in-video/.174172|url-status=live}}</ref> For the first 13 episodes of the sixth season, the opening theme is {{nihongo|"Hitamuki"|ひたむき||{{lit|Single-Minded}}}} by [[Super Beaver]], while the ending theme is "Sketch" by Kiro Akiyama.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=SUPER BEAVER, Kiro Akiyama Perform Theme Songs for My Hero Academia Anime's 6th Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-08-24/super-beaver-kiro-akiyama-perform-theme-songs-for-my-hero-academia-anime-6th-season/.188948|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 24, 2022|access-date=August 24, 2022|archive-date=August 24, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220824170753/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-08-24/super-beaver-kiro-akiyama-perform-theme-songs-for-my-hero-academia-anime-6th-season/.188948|url-status=live}}</ref> From episode 14 onwards, the opening theme is {{nihongo|"Bokurano"|ぼくらの||{{lit|Our}}}} by [[Eve (Japanese singer)|Eve]], while the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Kitakaze"|キタカゼ||{{lit|North Wind}}}} by Six Lounge.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Rock Band Six Lounge Performs New Ending Theme for My Hero Academia Anime|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-12-24/rock-band-six-lounge-performs-new-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime/.193299|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 24, 2022|access-date=December 24, 2022|archive-date=December 24, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221224201603/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-12-24/rock-band-six-lounge-performs-new-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime/.193299|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Eve Performs New Opening Theme for My Hero Academia Anime|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-01-07/eve-performs-new-opening-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime/.193621|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 7, 2023|access-date=January 7, 2023|archive-date=January 7, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230107223722/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-01-07/eve-performs-new-opening-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime/.193621|url-status=live}}</ref> For the first nine episodes of the seventh season, the opening theme is {{nihongo|"Tagatame"|誰我為||{{lit|For Someone's Sake}}}} by [[Toru Kitajima|TK from Ling Tosite Sigure]] and the ending theme is {{nihongo|"Tsubomi"|蕾||{{lit|Flower Bud}}}} by [[Omoinotake]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cayanan|first=Joanna|title=My Hero Academia Season 7's 2nd Video Unveils Opening Song|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-03-24/my-hero-academia-season-7-2nd-video-unveils-opening-song/.209170|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 24, 2024|access-date=March 24, 2024|archive-date=March 24, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240324091327/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-03-24/my-hero-academia-season-7-2nd-video-unveils-opening-song/.209170|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Omoinotake Performs Ending Theme for My Hero Academia Anime's 7th Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-04-13/omoinotake-performs-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime-7th-season/.209795|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 13, 2024|access-date=April 13, 2024|archive-date=April 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240413162531/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-04-13/omoinotake-performs-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime-7th-season/.209795|url-status=live}}</ref> From episode ten onwards, the opening theme is {{nihongo|"Curtain Call"|カーテンコール}} by [[Yuuri (singer-songwriter)|Yuuri]], while the ending theme is {{Nihongo|"Rokutōsei"|六等星||{{lit|Class 6 Star}}}} by Zarame.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia TV Anime Reveals New Opening, Ending Themes for 7th Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-07-13/my-hero-academia-tv-anime-reveals-new-opening-ending-themes-for-7th-season/.213171|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 13, 2024|access-date=July 13, 2024|archive-date=July 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240713141316/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-07-13/my-hero-academia-tv-anime-reveals-new-opening-ending-themes-for-7th-season/.213171|url-status=live}}</ref> For the eighth and final season, the opening theme is "The Revo" by Porno Graffitti, who previously provided the opening theme song "The Day" from the first season, and the ending theme is "I" by [[Bump of Chicken]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Cayanan|first=Joanna|title=Final My Hero Academia Season's English-Subtitled Trailer Unveils Porno Graffitti's Opening Song|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-08-17/final-my-hero-academia-season-english-subtitled-trailer-unveils-porno-graffitti-opening-song/.227730|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 17, 2025|access-date=August 17, 2025|archive-date=August 17, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250817131200/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-08-17/final-my-hero-academia-season-english-subtitled-trailer-unveils-porno-graffitti-opening-song/.227730|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Bump of Chicken Performs Ending Theme for My Hero Academia Anime's Final Season|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-09-27/bump-of-chicken-performs-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime-final-season/.229359|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 27, 2025|access-date=September 27, 2025|archive-date=September 27, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250927093301/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-09-27/bump-of-chicken-performs-ending-theme-for-my-hero-academia-anime-final-season/.229359|url-status=live}}</ref>

In November 2021, a concert event titled ''My Hero Academia Official Live Concert'' was held in [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hazra|first=Adriana|title=Anime NYC Hosts Composer Yuki Hayashi With My Hero Academia Performance|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-11-16/anime-nyc-hosts-composer-yuki-hayashi-with-my-hero-academia-performance/.179490|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 16, 2021|access-date=November 17, 2021|archive-date=November 22, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211122214503/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-11-16/anime-nyc-hosts-composer-yuki-hayashi-with-my-hero-academia-performance/.179490|url-status=live}}</ref> Another concert event, titled ''My Hero Academia Special Film Concert'', was held at [[Arena Tachikawa Tachihi]] on November 23, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Harding|first=Daryl|title=My Hero Academia Anime Classes Up in Special Concert Visual|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/news/latest/2023/10/18/my-hero-academia-anime-classes-up-in-special-concert-visual|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=October 10, 2023|access-date=December 7, 2023|archive-date=May 1, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240501055930/https://www.crunchyroll.com/news/latest/2023/10/18/my-hero-academia-anime-classes-up-in-special-concert-visual|url-status=live}}</ref> A two-day Plus Ultra concert event featuring the artists and bands from the series, titled ''ANI-ROCK FES. 2024 My Hero Academia PLUS ULTRA LIVE'', was held on February 24 and 25, 2024 at [[Yokohama Arena]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Harding|first=Daryl|title=My Hero Academia Rocks on With Plus Ultra Live 2-Day Concert Event|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/news/latest/2023/8/21/my-hero-academia-rocks-on-with-plus-ultra-live-2-day-concert-event|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=August 21, 2023|access-date=December 7, 2023|archive-date=November 29, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231129151817/https://www.crunchyroll.com/news/latest/2023/8/21/my-hero-academia-rocks-on-with-plus-ultra-live-2-day-concert-event|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Light novels ===
A [[light novel]] series, titled {{nihongo|''My Hero Academia: School Briefs''|僕のヒーローアカデミア 雄英白書|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Yūei Hakusho}}, written by Anri Yoshi, was released by Shueisha under its [[Jump (magazine line)#Jump J-Books|Jump J-Books]] imprint. It centers on Izuku Midoriya and his classmates of U.A. High in everyday school lives. The first volume was released on April 4, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア 雄英白書|url=https://j-books.shueisha.co.jp/books/bokunoheroacademia_01.html|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|access-date=January 5, 2021|language=ja|archive-date=February 2, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210202092329/https://j-books.shueisha.co.jp/books/bokunoheroacademia_01.html|url-status=live}}</ref> {{As of|df=US|2021|10|04|post=,}} six volumes have been published.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア 雄英白書 桜|url=https://j-books.shueisha.co.jp/books/bokunoheroacademia_06.html|publisher=[[Shueisha]]|access-date=October 4, 2021|language=ja|archive-date=June 18, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220618173145/https://j-books.shueisha.co.jp/books/bokunoheroacademia_06.html|url-status=live}}</ref> In North America, it has been licensed in English by Viz Media.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Viz Media to Release Anri Yoshi's My Hero Academia: School Briefs Novel Series|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-07-21/viz-media-to-release-anri-yoshi-my-hero-academia-school-briefs-novel-series/.134543|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 21, 2018|access-date=August 22, 2018|archive-date=August 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825044520/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-07-21/viz-media-to-release-anri-yoshi-my-hero-academia-school-briefs-novel-series/.134543|url-status=live}}</ref>

Light novels based on the four anime films were released on August 3, 2018, December 20, 2019, August 6, 2021, and August 2, 2024, also written by Anri Yoshi.<ref>''My Hero Academia'' light novel anime films:
* {{Cite book|language=ja|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア THE MOVIE ~2人の英雄 ~ (JUMP j BOOKS)|trans-title=''My Hero Academia Two Heroes'' (JUMP j BOOKS)|id={{ASIN|4087034585|country=jp}}}}
* {{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia -Heroes: Rising- Film Listed With Novel Version in December|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-10-28/my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-film-listed-with-novel-version-in-december/.152711|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 2, 2021|access-date=April 2, 2021|archive-date=January 25, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125101358/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-10-28/my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-film-listed-with-novel-version-in-december/.152711|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=''My Hero Academia World Heroes' Mission'' Film Listed With Novel|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-06-19/my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-film-listed-with-novel/.174065|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 19, 2021|access-date=July 28, 2021|archive-date=May 2, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220502074307/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-06-19/my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-film-listed-with-novel/.174065|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite book|language=ja|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア THE MOVIE ワールド ヒーローズ ミッション (JUMP j BOOKS)|trans-title=''My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission'' (JUMP j BOOKS)|id={{ASIN|4087035131|country=jp}}}}
* {{Cite book|language=ja|script-title=ja:僕のヒーローアカデミア THE MOVIE ユアネクスト (JUMP j BOOKS)|trans-title=''My Hero Academia: You're Next'' (JUMP j BOOKS)|id={{ASIN|4087035484|country=jp}}}}</ref>

=== Theatrical films ===
==== Anime ====
{{Main|My Hero Academia: Two Heroes{{!}}''My Hero Academia: Two Heroes''|My Hero Academia: Heroes Rising{{!}}''My Hero Academia: Heroes Rising''|My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission{{!}}''My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission''|My Hero Academia: You're Next{{!}}''My Hero Academia: You're Next''}}
An anime film was announced in December 2017 and features an original story set after the manga's "Final Exam" arc.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Gets Anime Film With Original Story in Summer 2018|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-12-10/my-hero-academia-gets-anime-film-with-original-story-in-summer-2018/.124951|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 10, 2017|access-date=December 10, 2017|archive-date=December 11, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211040254/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2017-12-10/my-hero-academia-gets-anime-film-with-original-story-in-summer-2018/.124951|url-status=live}}</ref> Titled ''My Hero Academia: Two Heroes'', the film had its world premiere at [[Anime Expo]] in Los Angeles on July 5, 2018,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Funimation, TOHO Host World Premiere of My Hero Academia: Two Heroes Film at Anime Expo|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-06-07/funimation-toho-host-world-premiere-of-my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-at-anime-expo/.132572|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=June 7, 2018|access-date=June 16, 2018|archive-date=June 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612165809/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-06-07/funimation-toho-host-world-premiere-of-my-hero-academia-two-heroes-film-at-anime-expo/.132572|url-status=live}}</ref> before a Japanese theatrical release on August 3, 2018, with the staff and cast from the anime series reprising their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Film Reveals Title, Story, August 3 Premiere|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-03-25/my-hero-academia-anime-film-reveals-title-story-august-3-premiere/.129389|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 25, 2018|access-date=March 25, 2018|archive-date=March 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326194434/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-03-25/my-hero-academia-anime-film-reveals-title-story-august-3-premiere/.129389|url-status=live}}</ref> The film has grossed over $33 million worldwide, and ended its theatrical run with $5.8 million to become the [[List of highest-grossing animated films in the United States and Canada|tenth highest-grossing animated film in the United States and Canada]] at that time.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ressler|first=Karen|title=My Hero Academia: Two Heroes Ends Theatrical Run With US$5.7 Million, Ranks #10 Among Domestic Anime Films|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-10-12/my-hero-academia-two-heroes-ends-theatrical-run-with-usd5.7-million-ranks-no.10-among-domestic-anime-films/.138093|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=October 13, 2018|access-date=September 21, 2021|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210921055818/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2018-10-12/my-hero-academia-two-heroes-ends-theatrical-run-with-usd5.7-million-ranks-no.10-among-domestic-anime-films/.138093|archive-date=September 21, 2021}}</ref>

On March 23, 2019, it was announced that a second animated film for the series was in production.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Pineda|first=Rafael Antonio|title=My Hero Academia Manga Gets 2nd Anime Film in Winter|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-03-22/my-hero-academia-manga-gets-2nd-anime-film-in-winter/.144780|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 23, 2019|access-date=March 23, 2019|archive-date=March 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323041621/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-03-22/my-hero-academia-manga-gets-2nd-anime-film-in-winter/.144780|url-status=live}}</ref> On July 7, 2019, the official Twitter account for ''My Hero Academia'' revealed the title as ''My Hero Academia: Heroes Rising''; the film was released in Japan on December 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=heroaca_movie|author=『僕のヒーローアカデミア THE MOVIE』公式|script-title=ja:ヒロアカ劇場版 最新作タイトル、公開日を解禁!!|date=July 7, 2019|number=1147831144475328512|language=Japanese|access-date=July 7, 2019}}</ref> The film takes place after the manga's "Meta Liberation Army" arc. It contains story elements that were once going to be used by [[Kōhei Horikoshi]] in the series finale.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Sherman|first=Jennifer|title=My Hero Academia Creator Teases Next Anime Film as Last One|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-07/my-hero-academia-creator-teases-next-anime-film-as-last-one/.148724|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 7, 2019|access-date=July 7, 2019|archive-date=July 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707150655/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-07-07/my-hero-academia-creator-teases-next-anime-film-as-last-one/.148724|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in North America on February 26, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia: Heroes Rising Film Opens in U.S., Canada on February 26|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-01-10/my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-film-opens-in-u.s-canada-on-february-26/.155224|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 10, 2020|access-date=February 20, 2020|archive-date=February 22, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222064514/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-01-10/my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-film-opens-in-u.s-canada-on-february-26/.155224|url-status=live}}</ref> The film has grossed $30 million worldwide, and surpassed ''My Hero Academia: Two Heroes'' during its ninth domestic gross weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Komatsu|first=Mikikazu|title=Japan Box Office: My Hero Academia Heroes: Rising Finally Surpasses 1st Film's Domestic Gross|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2020/02/17-1/japan-box-office-my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-finally-surpasses-1st-films-domestic-gross|website=[[Crunchyroll]]|date=February 18, 2020|access-date=February 20, 2020|archive-date=August 4, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240804214821/https://www.crunchyroll.com/news/latest/2020/2/17/japan-box-office-my-hero-academia-heroes-rising-finally-surpasses-1st-films-domestic-gross|url-status=live}}</ref>

On November 29, 2020, it was announced that a third animated film for the series was in production.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Gets 3rd Anime Film in Summer 2021|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-11-29/my-hero-academia-gets-3rd-anime-film-in-summer-2021/.166824|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 29, 2020|access-date=November 29, 2020|archive-date=November 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129150054/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-11-29/my-hero-academia-gets-3rd-anime-film-in-summer-2021/.166824|url-status=live}}</ref> The staff and cast from the previous two films reprised their roles.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=My Hero Academia's 3rd Anime Film Confirms Returning Main Staff|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-11-29/my-hero-academia-3rd-anime-film-confirms-returning-main-staff/.166840|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=November 29, 2020|access-date=November 29, 2020|archive-date=November 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201130012042/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2020-11-29/my-hero-academia-3rd-anime-film-confirms-returning-main-staff/.166840|url-status=live}}</ref> In the first episode of the series' fifth season, the film was revealed to be titled ''My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission''. The film was released in Japan on August 6, 2021,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia 3rd Anime Film's 1st Teaser Reveals Full Title, August 6 Opening|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-03-27/my-hero-academia-3rd-anime-film-1st-teaser-reveals-full-title-august-6-opening/.171168|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=March 27, 2021|access-date=March 27, 2021|archive-date=March 27, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210327123706/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-03-27/my-hero-academia-3rd-anime-film-1st-teaser-reveals-full-title-august-6-opening/.171168|url-status=live}}</ref> and premiered in the United States and Canada on October 29, 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=Funimation Screens ''My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission'' Anime Film in October|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-08-25/funimation-screens-my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-anime-film-in-october/.176650|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 25, 2021|access-date=August 25, 2021|archive-date=October 5, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211005011647/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-08-25/funimation-screens-my-hero-academia-world-heroes-mission-anime-film-in-october/.176650|url-status=live}}</ref> The film has grossed over $47 million worldwide, and became the [[List of Japanese films of 2021#Highest-grossing films|tenth highest-grossing domestic film of 2021 in Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loo|first=Egan|title=Final ''Evangelion'' Film Tops Japan's Box Office in 2021 So Far|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-12-29/final-evangelion-film-tops-japan-box-office-in-2021-so-far/.181107|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 29, 2021|access-date=January 13, 2022|archive-date=January 13, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220113144606/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-12-29/final-evangelion-film-tops-japan-box-office-in-2021-so-far/.181107|url-status=live}}</ref>

A fourth animated film was announced on August 6, 2023, taking place after the manga's "U.A. Traitor" arc.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime Gets 4th Film|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-08-06/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-4th-film/.201018|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=August 6, 2023|access-date=August 6, 2023|archive-date=August 6, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230806122253/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-08-06/my-hero-academia-anime-gets-4th-film/.201018|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 29, 2024, the film was revealed to be titled ''My Hero Academia: You're Next''. It was released in Japan on August 2, 2024,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 4th Film Opens in Summer 2024|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-12-16/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-film-opens-in-summer-2024/.205559|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=December 16, 2023|access-date=December 16, 2023|archive-date=December 16, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231216095114/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2023-12-16/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-film-opens-in-summer-2024/.205559|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=My Hero Academia Anime's 4th Film Reveals Trailer, Visual, Title, August 2 Premiere|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-01-29/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-film-reveals-trailer-visual-title-august-2-premiere/.206990|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 29, 2024|access-date=January 29, 2024|archive-date=January 29, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129160610/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-01-29/my-hero-academia-anime-4th-film-reveals-trailer-visual-title-august-2-premiere/.206990|url-status=live}}</ref> and began screening in the United States on October 11, 2024.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Tai|first=Anita|title=My Hero Academia: You're Next Film Screens in U.S. Theaters on October 11|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-07-06/my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-screens-in-u.s-theaters-on-october-11/.212923|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 6, 2024|access-date=July 7, 2024|archive-date=July 7, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240707025149/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2024-07-06/my-hero-academia-youre-next-film-screens-in-u.s-theaters-on-october-11/.212923|url-status=live}}</ref> The film has grossed over $32 million worldwide, and surpassed ''My Hero Academia: World Heroes' Mission'' as the highest-grossing film of the franchise during its tenth weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|script-title=ja:映画『ヒロアカ』興収35.2億円突破でシリーズ歴代1位「最高ヒット作に!」|url=https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2349645/full/|website=[[Oricon News]]|publisher=[[Oricon]]|date=October 16, 2024|access-date=October 18, 2024|language=ja|archive-date=November 6, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241106065009/https://www.oricon.co.jp/news/2349645/full/|url-status=live}}</ref> It also became the [[List of Japanese films of 2024#Highest-grossing films|tenth highest-grossing domestic film of 2024 in Japan]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=Detective Conan: The Million-dollar Pentagram, HAIKYU!! The Dumpster Battle Top Japan's Box Office in 2024|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-01-30/detective-conan-the-million-dollar-pentagram-haikyu-the-dumpster-battle-top-japan-box-office-in-2024/.220651|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 30, 2025|access-date=January 31, 2025|archive-date=January 31, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250131120814/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-01-30/detective-conan-the-million-dollar-pentagram-haikyu-the-dumpster-battle-top-japan-box-office-in-2024/.220651|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Live action ====
In October 2018, [[Legendary Entertainment]] acquired the rights to produce a [[live action]] adaptation of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hoffmeyer|first=Corey|title=My Hero Academia Live-Action Movie In Development At Legendary|url=https://screenrant.com/my-hero-academia-movie-legendary-toho/|website=[[Screen Rant]]|date=October 24, 2018|access-date=October 25, 2018|archive-date=October 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025080817/https://screenrant.com/my-hero-academia-movie-legendary-toho/|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2021, it was revealed to be directed by [[Shinsuke Sato]], with Alex Garcia and Jay Ashenfelter overseeing the adaptation, and Ryosuke Yoritomi representing the manga publisher Shueisha. Toho is set to distribute the film in Japan.<ref>{{Cite web|last=McNary|first=Dave|title='My Hero Academia' Live-Action Movie in the Works at Legendary|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/my-hero-academia-movie-legendary-1202992783/|author-link=Dave McNary|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 24, 2018|access-date=August 13, 2021|archive-date=February 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210228032255/https://variety.com/2018/film/asia/my-hero-academia-movie-legendary-1202992783/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title='My Hero Academia' Live-Action Movie Gets Director In 'Kingdom's Shinsuke Sato|url=https://deadline.com/2021/08/my-hero-academia-live-action-movie-shinsuke-sato-director-1234814520/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=August 13, 2021|access-date=August 13, 2021|archive-date=August 13, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210813211813/https://deadline.com/2021/08/my-hero-academia-live-action-movie-shinsuke-sato-director-1234814520/|url-status=live}}</ref> On December 12, 2022, [[Netflix]] announced that they had acquired the rights to the film with [[Joby Harold]] as screenwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Vlessing|first=Etan|title=Netflix Boards 'My Hero Academia' Live-Action Movie From Legendary|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/netflix-boards-my-hero-academia-live-action-movie-legendary-1235280318/|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 12, 2022|access-date=December 12, 2022|archive-date=December 12, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221212233817/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/netflix-boards-my-hero-academia-live-action-movie-legendary-1235280318/|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 9, 2025, it was announced that [[Jason Fuchs]] had been hired to rewrite the script and that Sato had been reaffirmed as director.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title='My Hero Academia' Live-Action Movie Nabs 'Welcome to Derry' Co-Creator as Writer (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/my-hero-academia-live-action-movie-1236366658/|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 9, 2025|access-date=September 9, 2025|archive-date=September 9, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250909233844/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/movies/movie-news/my-hero-academia-live-action-movie-1236366658/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Video games ===
==== Console games ====
{{Main|My Hero Academia: Battle for All{{!}}''My Hero Academia: Battle for All''|My Hero One's Justice{{!}}''My Hero One's Justice''|My Hero One's Justice 2{{!}}''My Hero One's Justice 2''|My Hero Ultra Rumble{{!}}''My Hero Ultra Rumble''}}
A video game based on the anime, {{nihongo4|''[[My Hero Academia: Battle for All]]''|僕のヒーローアカデミア バトル・フォー・オール|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Batoru fō Ōru}}, was announced in November 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Sato|title=My Hero Academia Game Announced For Nintendo 3DS|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2015/11/18/my-hero-academia-game-announced-for-nintendo-3ds/|website=[[Siliconera]]|date=November 18, 2015|access-date=November 18, 2015|archive-date=November 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119145732/http://www.siliconera.com/2015/11/18/my-hero-academia-game-announced-for-nintendo-3ds/|url-status=dead}}</ref> The game was developed by [[Dimps]] and published by [[Bandai Namco Entertainment]] for the [[Nintendo 3DS]], where it released in Japan on May 19, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hallmark|first=Kyle|title=My Hero Academia: Battle for All 3DS Game's Play Videos Preview Characters|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-04-04/my-hero-academia-battle-for-all-3ds-game-play-videos-preview-characters/.100628|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=April 4, 2016|access-date=April 5, 2016|archive-date=April 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405162758/http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-04-04/my-hero-academia-battle-for-all-3ds-game-play-videos-preview-characters/.100628|url-status=live}}</ref>

''My Hero Academia'' has also received four video games developed by Byking and published by Bandai Namco Entertainment. The first, titled {{Nihongo4|''[[My Hero One's Justice]]''|僕のヒーローアカデミア {{Ruby|One's Justice|ワンズ ジャスティス}}|Boku no Hīrō Akademia: Wanzu Jasutisu}}, was released for [[PlayStation 4]], [[Nintendo Switch]], [[Windows]], and [[Xbox One]] on October 26, 2018.<ref>''My Hero One's Justice'':
* {{Cite web|title=My Hero One's Justice|url=https://www.bandainamcoent.com/games/my-hero-ones-justice|publisher=[[Bandai Namco Entertainment|Bandai Namco Entertainment America]]|access-date=April 16, 2018|archive-date=April 17, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180417105902/https://www.bandainamcoent.com/games/my-hero-ones-justice|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|last=Dayus|first=Oscar|title=PS4 And Nintendo Switch My Hero Academia Game Revealed|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ps4-and-nintendo-switch-my-hero-academia-game-reve/1100-6455289/|website=[[GameSpot]]|date=November 30, 2017|access-date=November 30, 2017|archive-date=December 23, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171223070624/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/ps4-and-nintendo-switch-my-hero-academia-game-reve/1100-6455289/|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|last=Romano|first=Sal|title=My Hero Academia: One's Justice coming west for PS4, Xbox One, Switch, and PC in 2018|url=https://gematsu.com/2017/12/hero-academia-ones-justice-coming-west-ps4-xbox-one-switch-pc-2018|website=Gematsu|date=December 18, 2017|access-date=December 18, 2017|archive-date=December 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222051052/https://gematsu.com/2017/12/hero-academia-ones-justice-coming-west-ps4-xbox-one-switch-pc-2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The game has sold over 500,000 units worldwide by January 2019.<ref>{{Cite magazine|script-title=ja:『僕のヒーローアカデミア One's Justice』全世界累計出荷本数50万本突破記念！ ダウンロード版30%OFFセールが実施|url=https://www.famitsu.com/news/201901/31171286.html|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|date=January 31, 2019|access-date=March 23, 2019|language=ja|archive-date=March 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324024212/https://www.famitsu.com/news/201901/31171286.html|url-status=live}}</ref> A sequel, {{nihongo4|''[[My Hero One's Justice 2]]''|僕のヒーローアカデミア {{ruby|One's Justice|ワンズ ジャスティス}}2|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Wanzu Jasutisu Tsū}}, was released on Nintendo Switch, PlayStation 4, Windows, and Xbox One on March 12, 2020, in Japan and worldwide in the following day.<ref>''My Hero One's Justice 2'':
* {{Cite web|last=Romano|first=Sal|title=My Hero One's Justice 2 announced for PS4, Xbox One, and Switch|url=https://gematsu.com/2019/09/my-hero-ones-justice-2-announced-for-ps4-xbox-one-and-switch|website=Gematsu|date=September 26, 2019|access-date=September 27, 2019|archive-date=September 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190926135130/https://gematsu.com/2019/09/my-hero-ones-justice-2-announced-for-ps4-xbox-one-and-switch|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|author=Sato|title=My Hero One's Justice 2 Adds Sir Nighteye, Releases In Japan On March 12, 2020 (Update)|url=https://www.siliconera.com/my-hero-ones-justice-2-adds-sir-nighteye-releases-in-japan-on-march-12-2020/|website=[[Siliconera]]|date=November 28, 2019|access-date=November 29, 2019|archive-date=February 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229060737/https://www.siliconera.com/my-hero-ones-justice-2-adds-sir-nighteye-releases-in-japan-on-march-12-2020/|url-status=live}}</ref> The third, a free-to-play battle royale action game, titled {{nihongo|''[[My Hero Ultra Rumble]]''|僕のヒーローアカデミア {{ruby|ULTRA RUMBLE|ウルトラ ランブル}}|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Urutora Ranburu}}, was released for Nintendo Switch, PlayStation 4, Windows and Xbox One on September 28, 2023.<ref>''My Hero Ultra Rumble'':
* {{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=My Hero Academia Ultra Rumble Game Announced|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-01-16/my-hero-academia-ultra-rumble-game-announced/.181551|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=January 16, 2022|access-date=January 16, 2022|archive-date=January 16, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220116163631/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-01-16/my-hero-academia-ultra-rumble-game-announced/.181551|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|last=Hodgkins|first=Crystalyn|title=Bandai Namco Ent. to Release My Hero Ultra Rumble Game in English|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-07-02/bandai-namco-ent-to-release-my-hero-ultra-rumble-game-in-english/.187289|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=July 2, 2022|access-date=July 2, 2022|archive-date=July 2, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220702190711/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-07-02/bandai-namco-ent-to-release-my-hero-ultra-rumble-game-in-english/.187289|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|last=Romano|first=Sal|title=My Hero Ultra Rumble launches September 28|url=https://www.gematsu.com/2023/09/my-hero-ultra-rumble-launches-september-28|website=Gematsu|date=September 20, 2023|access-date=September 20, 2023|archive-date=September 27, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230927052007/https://www.gematsu.com/2023/09/my-hero-ultra-rumble-launches-september-28|url-status=live}}</ref> The fourth, a sequel to ''One's Justice 2'' titled ''My Hero Academia: All's Justice'', is set to be released on [[PlayStation 5]], Windows, and [[Xbox Series X/S]] on February 5, 2026, in Japan and worldwide in the following day.<ref>''My Hero Academia: All's Justice'':
* {{Cite web|last=Romano|first=Sal|title=My Hero Academia: All's Justice announced for PS5, Xbox Series, and PC|url=https://www.gematsu.com/2025/07/my-hero-academia-alls-justice-announced-for-ps5-xbox-series-and-pc|website=Gematsu|date=July 2, 2025|access-date=July 2, 2025|archive-date=July 2, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250702222513/https://www.gematsu.com/2025/07/my-hero-academia-alls-justice-announced-for-ps5-xbox-series-and-pc|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=My Hero Academia: All's Justice Game's Trailer Reveals February 6 Release|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-09-30/my-hero-academia-all-justice-game-trailer-reveals-february-6-release/.229476|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=September 30, 2025|access-date=September 30, 2025|archive-date=September 30, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250930224959/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2025-09-30/my-hero-academia-all-justice-game-trailer-reveals-february-6-release/.229476|url-status=live}}
* {{Cite web|last=Lada|first=Jenni|title=My Hero Academia: All's Justice Game Releases in February|url=https://www.siliconera.com/my-hero-academia-alls-justice-game-releases-in-february/|website=[[Siliconera]]|date=September 30, 2025|access-date=September 30, 2025|archive-date=September 30, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250930224051/https://www.siliconera.com/my-hero-academia-alls-justice-game-releases-in-february/|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Mobile games ====
Three mobile games have been released for [[iOS]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]].<ref name="MHA TSH"/><ref name="MHUI"/> ''My Hero Academia: The Strongest Hero'' was released in North America and several other mostly English-speaking countries in late May 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Ankers-Range|first=Adele|title=My Hero Academia: The Strongest Hero Officially Launches With a New Trailer|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/my-hero-academia-the-strongest-hero-mobile-game-launch-trailer-released|website=[[IGN]]|date=May 19, 2021|access-date=June 17, 2021|archive-date=May 19, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210519201322/https://www.ign.com/articles/my-hero-academia-the-strongest-hero-mobile-game-launch-trailer-released|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="MHA TSH">{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=My Hero Academia: The Strongest Hero Smartphone Game Launches for iOS, Android|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-05-19/my-hero-academia-the-strongest-hero-smartphone-game-launches-for-ios-android/.172978|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=May 19, 2021|access-date=June 17, 2021|archive-date=May 19, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210519211941/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2021-05-19/my-hero-academia-the-strongest-hero-smartphone-game-launches-for-ios-android/.172978|url-status=live}}</ref> {{nihongo|''My Hero Ultra Impact''|僕のヒーローアカデミア {{ruby|ULTRA IMPACT|ウルトラ インパクト}}|Boku no Hīrō Akademia Urutora Inpakuto}} was released in February 2022.<ref name="MHUI">{{Cite web|last=Mateo|first=Alex|title=My Hero Ultra Impact Game Launches for iOS, Android|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-02-10/my-hero-ultra-impact-game-launches-for-ios-android/.182490|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 10, 2022|access-date=February 10, 2022|archive-date=February 10, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220210222347/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2022-02-10/my-hero-ultra-impact-game-launches-for-ios-android/.182490|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Crossovers ====
Izuku Midoriya, [[All Might]], Katsuki Bakugo, and Shoto Todoroki appeared as playable characters in the 2018 [[Crossover (fiction)|crossover]] [[fighting game]] ''[[Jump Force]]''.<ref name="mha">''Jump Force'' playable characters:
