=== Unit 731 controversy ===
In early 2020, the series caused a controversy in South Korea and China for a character's name allegedly referencing [[Unit 731]],<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loveridge|first=Lynzee|title=My Hero Academia Character Gets Name Change Following Controversy|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-03/my-hero-academia-character-gets-name-change-following-controversy/.156076|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 3, 2020|access-date=February 4, 2020|quote=The character's original given name was revealed in chapter 259 as "Maruta Shiga." "Maruta" refers to the code-name for human experimentation undertaken by the Imperial Japanese Army's Unit 731 during the Second Sino-Japanese War of World War II. The Chinese victims of the experiments were called "maruta," the Japanese word for "logs" as a reference to the facilities cover story that it was a lumber mill. Victims, including children, the elderly, pregnant women, and the mentally handicapped, were purposefully infected with diseases, dissected, lobotomized, and amputated while still alive.|archive-date=June 20, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230620065927/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-03/my-hero-academia-character-gets-name-change-following-controversy/.156076|url-status=live}}</ref> an infamous Imperial Japanese army unit known its immensely brutal and inhumane experiments on [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] (POWs), including the [[Vivisection|vivisecting]] of captured Chinese, Korean, and Russian soldiers and civilians. In response, the series has been removed from digital platforms in China, and the character's name was changed to no longer reference Unit 731.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loveridge|first=Lynzee|title=My Hero Academia Manga, Anime Removed from Chinese Digital Platforms|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-05/my-hero-academia-manga-anime-removed-from-chinese-digital-platforms/.156125|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 5, 2020|access-date=February 7, 2020|quote=The manga character's name reopening wounds in China and Korea that lead to the series' manga and anime being pulled from [[bilibili]] and [[Tencent]] and the possible cancellation of the mobile game ''My Hero Academia: Strongest Hero'' by Chinese studio Xin Yuan.|archive-date=February 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206022020/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-05/my-hero-academia-manga-anime-removed-from-chinese-digital-platforms/.156125|url-status=live}}</ref> A day prior, both ''[[Weekly Shōnen Jump]]'' manga magazine publisher [[Shueisha]] and the manga's author Kōhei Horikoshi issued individual apology statements on Twitter.<ref name="Apology">{{Cite web|last=Loveridge|first=Lynzee|title=Shueisha Issues Formal Apology for My Hero Academia Character's Name|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-07/shueisha-issues-formal-apology-for-my-hero-academia-character-name/.156239|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 7, 2020|access-date=February 8, 2020|archive-date=January 11, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111024034/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-07/shueisha-issues-formal-apology-for-my-hero-academia-character-name/.156239|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the aftermath of the manga's removal from its services in China, the English-language news service Abacus reached out to [[bilibili]] and [[Tencent]] for its request. The former stated that the removal was "in accordance with China's policies" but declined to comment further, while the latter did not respond to Abacus' request for comment.<ref name="Apology"/> The character's name was changed again in the digital version of ''Weekly Shōnen Jump'' following the backlash. Shueisha promised that "going forward, we intend to devote our energies toward deepening our understanding of a variety of historical and cultural matters." Both the publisher and manga's creator reiterated that the reference to [[war crimes]] within the character's name was wholly unintentional.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Loveridge|first=Lynzee|title=My Hero Academia Manga Updated With Villain's New Name|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-10/my-hero-academia-manga-updated-with-villain-new-name/.156305|website=[[Anime News Network]]|date=February 10, 2020|access-date=February 11, 2020|quote=The character's real name was changed to Kyudai Garaki in the update. The new name maintains elements from creator Kōhei Horikoshi's original name; "Kyudai" is written with the kanji for "ball" and "big" and "Garaki" takes the last three syllables of the villain's mentor's name "Shigaraki" while also including the kanji for "tree."|archive-date=June 2, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220602060139/https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/interest/2020-02-10/my-hero-academia-manga-updated-with-villain-new-name/.156305|url-status=live}}</ref>

Following the controversy, the work has often been regarded as an anti-China anime. In June 2025, there were multiple reports of cosplayers portraying characters from the work being attacked in China.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Cos日漫角色遭小粉紅攻擊！外網：和紅衛兵無異 - 桃園電子報|url=https://tyenews.com/2025/06/867400/|website=Taoyuan e-News|date=June 10, 2025|access-date=August 11, 2025|language=zh-TW|archive-date=June 24, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250624095213/https://tyenews.com/2025/06/867400/|url-status=live}}</p><p>{{Cite web|title=《我的英雄學院》中國Coser發生多起遭圍攻事件，因為辱華事件遭扯假髮與嘲笑|url=https://tw.news.yahoo.com/《我的英雄學院》中國coser發生多起遭圍攻事件，因為辱華事件遭扯假髮與嘲笑-035839640.html|website=Yahoo News|date=June 10, 2025|access-date=August 11, 2025|language=zh-Hant-TW|archive-date=August 25, 2025|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250825111230/https://tw.news.yahoo.com/《我的英雄學院》中國coser發生多起遭圍攻事件，因為辱華事件遭扯假髮與嘲笑-035839640.html|url-status=live}}</p></ref>

